advanced.name: advanced

revisions.description: Multiplied lDiskAvgDiskSecPerRead, lDiskAvgDiskSecPerTransfer, lDiskAvgDiskSecPerWrite, pDiskAvgDiskSecPerRead, pDiskAvgDiskSecPerTransfer, and pDiskAvgDiskSecPerWrite by 1000000 since these values are commonly fractional (less than 1).
Added additional entries which are available in Windows Server 2008.
Updated the description fields based on the description in Microsoft Windows Server 2008.
Added memoryCommitLimitKBytes and memoryCommitLimitMBytes to support greater than 32-bit memoryCommitLimits.

Multiplied lDiskAvgDiskQueueLength, lDiskAvgDiskReadQueueLength, lDiskAvgDiskWriteQueueLength, lDiskAvgDiskSecPerRead, lDiskAvgDiskSecPerTransfer, lDiskAvgDiskSecPerWrite, pDiskAvgDiskQueueLength, pDiskAvgDiskReadQueueLength, pDiskAvgDiskWriteQueueLength, pDiskAvgDiskSecPerRead, pDiskAvgDiskSecPerTransfer, and pDiskAvgDiskSecPerWrite by 1000 since these values are commonly fractional (less than 1).
Added new performance counters which are in Windows Vista.
.NET CLR Data is an instance type counter. Changed dotNETCLRData to a SNMP table.
.NET CLR Networking is an instance type counter. Changed dotNETCLRNetworking to a SNMP table.
Changed the syntax of the datapoints from integer to gauge.
The initial revision of this MIB module.

acsPerRsvpServiceTable.name: acsPerRsvpServiceTable
acsPerRsvpServiceTable.description: The ACS/RSVP Service performance object counters report statistics about Resource Reservation Protocol (RSVP) and Quality of Service (QoS) Admission Control (ACS) activity, flow, bandwidth, RSVP messages sent, and so on. The ACS/RSVP Service object is available if QoS Admission Control is installed, even if the service is not running.

acsPerRsvpServiceEntry.description: Performance information for one particular instance of 'ACS/RSVP Service' object.

acsPerRsvpSvcFailedQoSRequests.name: acsPerRsvpSvcFailedQoSRequests
acsPerRsvpSvcFailedQoSRequests.description: The number of QoS requests generated by QoS-enabled applications that have been rejected by the ACS/RSVP service. Failed QoS requests can be caused by invalid QoS requests.

aspDotNET.name: aspDotNET
aspDotNET.description: ASP.NET supports the following ASP.NET system performance counters. These aggregate information for all ASP.NET applications on a Web server computer, or they apply generally to a system of ASP.NET servers running the same applications. These can include Web farms and Web gardens.

adnApplicationRestarts.name: adnApplicationRestarts
adnApplicationRestarts.description: Number of times the application has been restarted during the web server's lifetime.

adnApplicationsRunning.name: adnApplicationsRunning
adnApplicationsRunning.description: Number of currently running web applications.

adnRequestExecutionTime.name: adnRequestExecutionTime
adnRequestExecutionTime.description: The number of milliseconds that it took to execute the most recent request.

adnRequestWaitTime.name: adnRequestWaitTime
adnRequestWaitTime.description: The number of milliseconds the most recent request was waiting in the queue.

adnRequestsCurrent.name: adnRequestsCurrent
adnRequestsCurrent.description: The current number of requests, including those that are queued, currently executing, or waiting to be written to the client. Under the ASP.NET process model, when this counter exceeds the requestQueueLimit defined in the processModel configuration section, ASP.NET will begin rejecting requests.

adnRequestsDisconnected.name: adnRequestsDisconnected
adnRequestsDisconnected.description: The number of requests disconnected due to communication errors or user terminated.

adnRequestsQueued.name: adnRequestsQueued
adnRequestsQueued.description: The number of requests waiting to be processed.

adnRequestsRejected.name: adnRequestsRejected
adnRequestsRejected.description: The number of requests rejected because the request queue was full.

adnStateServerSessionsAbandoned.name: adnStateServerSessionsAbandoned
adnStateServerSessionsAbandoned.description: The number of sessions that have been explicitly abandoned.

adnStateServerSessionsActive.name: adnStateServerSessionsActive
adnStateServerSessionsActive.description: The current number of sessions currently active.

adnStateServerSessionsTimedOut.name: adnStateServerSessionsTimedOut
adnStateServerSessionsTimedOut.description: The number of sessions timed out.

adnWorkerProcessRestarts.name: adnWorkerProcessRestarts
adnWorkerProcessRestarts.description: Number of times a worker process has restarted on the machine.

adnWorkerProcessesRunning.name: adnWorkerProcessesRunning
adnWorkerProcessesRunning.description: Number of worker processes running on the machine.

adnAuditFailureEventsRaised.name: adnAuditFailureEventsRaised
adnAuditFailureEventsRaised.description: Number of audit failures in the application since it was started.

adnAuditSuccessEventsRaised.name: adnAuditSuccessEventsRaised
adnAuditSuccessEventsRaised.description: Number of audit successes in the application since it was started.

adnErrorEventsRaised.name: adnErrorEventsRaised
adnErrorEventsRaised.description: Number of error events raised since the application was started.

adnInfrastructErrorEventsRaised.name: adnInfrastructErrorEventsRaised
adnInfrastructErrorEventsRaised.description: Number of HTTP error events raised since the application was started.

adnRequestErrorEventsRaised.name: adnRequestErrorEventsRaised
adnRequestErrorEventsRaised.description: Number of runtime error events raised since the application was started.

aspDotNETApplicationsTable.name: aspDotNETApplicationsTable
aspDotNETApplicationsTable.description: ASP.NET supports the following application performance counters, which you can use to monitor the performance of a single instance of an ASP.NET application. A unique instance appears for these counters, named __Total__, which aggregates counters for all applications on a Web server (similar to the global counters described in the first section of this topic). The __Total__ instance is always available. The counters will display zero when no applications are present on the server.

aspDotNETApplicationsEntry.name: aspDotNETApplicationsEntry
aspDotNETApplicationsEntry.description: Performance information for one particular instance of 'ASP.NET Applications' object.

adnApplCachePrcntMchneMemLimUsed.name: adnApplCachePrcntMchneMemLimUsed
adnApplCachePrcntMchneMemLimUsed.description: The amount of physical memory used by the machine divided by the physical memory limit for the cache, as a percentage. When this reaches 100%, half of the cache entries will be forcibly removed. The __Total__ instance is the average of all instances, and therefore cannot be used to determine when cache entries will be forcibly removed.

adnApplCachePrcntPrcMemLimitUsed.name: adnApplCachePrcntPrcMemLimitUsed
adnApplCachePrcntPrcMemLimitUsed.description: The value of private bytes for the worker process divided by the private bytes memory limit for the cache, as a percentage. When this reaches 100%, half of the cache entries will be forcibly removed. The __Total__ instance is the average of all instances, and therefore cannot be used to determine when cache entries will be forcibly removed.

adnApplOutputCacheTrims.name: adnApplOutputCacheTrims
adnApplOutputCacheTrims.description: Total number of entries forcibly removed from the cache due to memory pressure that were originally inserted into the cache by the output cache feature.

browserAnnouncementsTotalPerSec.description: Announcements Total/sec is the sum of Announcements Server/sec and Announcements Domain/sec.

browserDuplicateMasterAnnounce.name: browserDuplicateMasterAnnounce
browserDuplicateMasterAnnounce.description: Duplicate Master Announcements indicates the number of times that the master browser has detected another master browser on the same domain.

browserElectionPacketsPerSec.name: browserElectionPacketsPerSec
browserElectionPacketsPerSec.description: Election Packets/sec is the rate at which browser election packets have been received by this workstation.

browserEnumerationsDomainPerSec.name: browserEnumerationsDomainPerSec
browserEnumerationsDomainPerSec.description: Enumerations Domain/sec is the rate at which domain browse requests have been processed by this workstation.

browserEnumerationsOtherPerSec.name: browserEnumerationsOtherPerSec
browserEnumerationsOtherPerSec.description: Enumerations Other/sec is the rate at which browse requests processed by this workstation are not domain or server browse requests.

browserEnumerationsServerPerSec.name: browserEnumerationsServerPerSec
browserEnumerationsServerPerSec.description: Enumerations Server/sec is the rate at which server browse requests have been processed by this workstation.

browserEnumerationsTotalPerSec.name: browserEnumerationsTotalPerSec
browserEnumerationsTotalPerSec.description: Enumerations Total/sec is the rate at which browse requests have been processed by this workstation. This is the sum of Enumerations Server/sec, Enumerations Domain/sec, and Enumerations Other/sec.

browserIllegalDatagramsPerSec.name: browserIllegalDatagramsPerSec
browserIllegalDatagramsPerSec.description: Illegal Datagrams/sec is the rate at which incorrectly formatted datagrams have been received by the workstation.

browserMailslotAllocationsFailed.name: browserMailslotAllocationsFailed
browserMailslotAllocationsFailed.description: Mailslot Allocations Failed is the number of times the datagram receiver has failed to allocate a buffer to hold a user mailslot write.

browserMailslotOpensFailedPerSec.name: browserMailslotOpensFailedPerSec
browserMailslotOpensFailedPerSec.description: Mailslot Opens Failed/sec indicates the rate at which mailslot messages to be delivered to mailslots that are not present are received by this workstation.

browserMailslotReceivesFailed.name: browserMailslotReceivesFailed
browserMailslotReceivesFailed.description: Mailslot Receives Failed indicates the number of mailslot messages that could not be received due to transport failures.

browserMailslotWritesFailed.name: browserMailslotWritesFailed
browserMailslotWritesFailed.description: Mailslot Writes Failed is the total number of mailslot messages that have been successfully received, but that could not be written to the mailslot.

browserMailslotWritesPerSec.name: browserMailslotWritesPerSec
browserMailslotWritesPerSec.description: Mailslot Writes/sec is the rate at which mailslot messages have been successfully received.

browserMissedMailslotDatagrams.name: browserMissedMailslotDatagrams
browserMissedMailslotDatagrams.description: Missed Mailslot Datagrams is the number of Mailslot Datagrams that have been discarded due to configuration or allocation limits.

browserMissedServerAnnouncements.name: browserMissedServerAnnouncements
browserMissedServerAnnouncements.description: Missed Server Announcements is the number of server announcements that have been missed due to configuration or allocation limits.

browserMissedServerListRequests.name: browserMissedServerListRequests
browserMissedServerListRequests.description: Missed Server List Requests is the number of requests to retrieve a list of browser servers that were received by this workstation, but could not be processed.

browserServerAllocFailedPerSec.name: browserServerAllocFailedPerSec
browserServerAllocFailedPerSec.description: Server Announce Allocations Failed/sec is the rate at which server (or domain) announcements have failed due to lack of memory.

browserServerListRequestsPerSec.name: browserServerListRequestsPerSec
browserServerListRequestsPerSec.description: Server List Requests/sec is the rate at which requests to retrieve a list of browser servers have been processed by this workstation.

cache.name: cache
cache.description: The Cache performance object consists of counters that monitor the file system cache, an area of physical memory that stores recently used data as long as possible to permit access to the data without having to read from the disk. Because applications typically use the cache, the cache is monitored as an indicator of application input/output (I/O) operations. When memory is plentiful, the cache can grow, but when memory is scarce, the cache can become too small to be effective.

cacheAsyncCopyReadsPerSec.name: cacheAsyncCopyReadsPerSec
cacheAsyncCopyReadsPerSec.description: Async Copy Reads/sec is the frequency of reads from pages of the file system cache that involve a memory copy of the data from the cache to the application's buffer. The application will regain control immediately even if the disk must be accessed to retrieve the page.

cacheAsyncDataMapsPerSec.name: cacheAsyncDataMapsPerSec
cacheAsyncDataMapsPerSec.description: Async Data Maps/sec is the frequency that an application using a file system, such as NTFS, to map a page of a file into the file system cache to read the page, and does not wait for the page to be retrieved if it is not in main memory.

cacheAsyncFastReadsPerSec.name: cacheAsyncFastReadsPerSec
cacheAsyncFastReadsPerSec.description: Async Fast Reads/sec is the frequency of reads from the file system cache that bypass the installed file system and retrieve the data directly from the cache. Normally, file I/O requests will invoke the appropriate file system to retrieve data from a file, but this path permits data to be retrieved from the cache directly (without file system involvement) if the data is in the cache. Even if the data is not in the cache, one invocation of the file system is avoided. If the data is not in the cache, the request (application program call) will not wait until the data has been retrieved from disk, but will get control immediately.

cacheAsyncMDLReadsPerSec.name: cacheAsyncMDLReadsPerSec
cacheAsyncMDLReadsPerSec.description: Async MDL Reads/sec is the frequency of reads from the file system cache that use a Memory Descriptor List (MDL) to access the pages. The MDL contains the physical address of each page in the transfer, thus permitting Direct Memory Access (DMA) of the pages. If the accessed page(s) are not in main memory, the calling application program will not wait for the pages to fault in from disk.

cacheAsyncPinReadsPerSec.name: cacheAsyncPinReadsPerSec
cacheAsyncPinReadsPerSec.description: Async Pin Reads/sec is the frequency of reading data into the file system cache preparatory to writing the data back to disk. Pages read in this fashion are pinned in memory at the completion of the read. The file system will regain control immediately even if the disk must be accessed to retrieve the page. While pinned, a page's physical address will not be altered.

cacheCopyReadHitsPercent.name: cacheCopyReadHitsPercent
cacheCopyReadHitsPercent.description: Copy Read Hits is the percentage of cache copy read requests that hit the cache, that is, they did not require a disk read in order to provide access to the page in the cache. A copy read is a file read operation that is satisfied by a memory copy from a page in the cache to the application's buffer. The LAN Redirector uses this method for retrieving information from the cache, as does the LAN Server for small transfers. This is a method used by the disk file systems as well.

cacheCopyReadsPerSec.name: cacheCopyReadsPerSec
cacheCopyReadsPerSec.description: Copy Reads/sec is the frequency of reads from pages of the file system cache that involve a memory copy of the data from the cache to the application's buffer. The LAN Redirector uses this method for retrieving information from the file system cache, as does the LAN Server for small transfers. This is a method used by the disk file systems as well.

cacheDataFlushPagesPerSec.name: cacheDataFlushPagesPerSec
cacheDataFlushPagesPerSec.description: Data Flush Pages/sec is the number of pages the file system cache has flushed to disk as a result of a request to flush or to satisfy a write-through file write request. More than one page can be transferred on each flush operation.

cacheDataFlushesPerSec.name: cacheDataFlushesPerSec
cacheDataFlushesPerSec.description: Data Flushes/sec is the rate at which the file system cache has flushed its contents to disk as the result of a request to flush or to satisfy a write-through file write request. More than one page can be transferred on each flush operation.

cacheDataMapHitsPercent.name: cacheDataMapHitsPercent
cacheDataMapHitsPercent.description: Data Map Hits is the percentage of data maps in the file system cache that could be resolved without having to retrieve a page from the disk, because the page was already in physical memory.

cacheDataMapPinsPerSec.name: cacheDataMapPinsPerSec
cacheDataMapPinsPerSec.description: Data Map Pins/sec is the frequency of data maps in the file system cache that resulted in pinning a page in main memory, an action usually preparatory to writing to the file on disk. While pinned, a page's physical address in main memory and virtual address in the file system cache will not be altered.

cacheDataMapsPerSec.name: cacheDataMapsPerSec
cacheDataMapsPerSec.description: Data Maps/sec is the frequency that a file system such as NTFS, maps a page of a file into the file system cache to read the page.

cacheFastReadNotPossiblesPerSec.name: cacheFastReadNotPossiblesPerSec
cacheFastReadNotPossiblesPerSec.description: Fast Read Not Possibles/sec is the frequency of attempts by an Application Program Interface (API) function call to bypass the file system to get to data in the file system cache that could not be honored without invoking the file system.

cacheFastReadResourceMissPerSec.name: cacheFastReadResourceMissPerSec
cacheFastReadResourceMissPerSec.description: Fast Read Resource Misses/sec is the frequency of cache misses necessitated by the lack of available resources to satisfy the request.

cacheFastReadsPerSec.name: cacheFastReadsPerSec
cacheFastReadsPerSec.description: Fast Reads/sec is the frequency of reads from the file system cache that bypass the installed file system and retrieve the data directly from the cache. Normally, file I/O requests invoke the appropriate file system to retrieve data from a file, but this path permits direct retrieval of data from the cache without file system involvement if the data is in the cache. Even if the data is not in the cache, one invocation of the file system is avoided.

cacheLazyWriteFlushesPerSec.name: cacheLazyWriteFlushesPerSec
cacheLazyWriteFlushesPerSec.description: Lazy Write Flushes/sec is the rate at which the Lazy Writer thread has written to disk. Lazy Writing is the process of updating the disk after the page has been changed in memory, so that the application that changed the file does not have to wait for the disk write to be complete before proceeding. More than one page can be transferred by each write operation.

cacheLazyWritePagesPerSec.name: cacheLazyWritePagesPerSec
cacheLazyWritePagesPerSec.description: Lazy Write Pages/sec is the rate at which the Lazy Writer thread has written to disk. Lazy Writing is the process of updating the disk after the page has been changed in memory, so that the application that changed the file does not have to wait for the disk write to be complete before proceeding. More than one page can be transferred on a single disk write operation.

cacheMDLReadHitsPercent.name: cacheMDLReadHitsPercent
cacheMDLReadHitsPercent.description: MDL Read Hits is the percentage of Memory Descriptor List (MDL) Read requests to the file system cache that hit the cache, i.e., did not require disk accesses in order to provide memory access to the page(s) in the cache.

cacheMDLReadsPerSec.name: cacheMDLReadsPerSec
cacheMDLReadsPerSec.description: MDL Reads/sec is the frequency of reads from the file system cache that use a Memory Descriptor List (MDL) to access the data. The MDL contains the physical address of each page involved in the transfer, and thus can employ a hardware Direct Memory Access (DMA) device to effect the copy. The LAN Server uses this method for large transfers out of the server.

cachePinReadHitsPercent.name: cachePinReadHitsPercent
cachePinReadHitsPercent.description: Pin Read Hits is the percentage of pin read requests that hit the file system cache, i.e., did not require a disk read in order to provide access to the page in the file system cache. While pinned, a page's physical address in the file system cache will not be altered. The LAN Redirector uses this method for retrieving data from the cache, as does the LAN Server for small transfers. This is usually the method used by the disk file systems as well.

cachePinReadsPerSec.name: cachePinReadsPerSec
cachePinReadsPerSec.description: Pin Reads/sec is the frequency of reading data into the file system cache preparatory to writing the data back to disk. Pages read in this fashion are pinned in memory at the completion of the read. While pinned, a page's physical address in the file system cache will not be altered.

cacheReadAheadsPerSec.name: cacheReadAheadsPerSec
cacheReadAheadsPerSec.description: Read Aheads/sec is the frequency of reads from the file system cache in which the Cache detects sequential access to a file. The read aheads permit the data to be transferred in larger blocks than those being requested by the application, reducing the overhead per access.

cacheSyncCopyReadsPerSec.name: cacheSyncCopyReadsPerSec
cacheSyncCopyReadsPerSec.description: Sync Copy Reads/sec is the frequency of reads from pages of the file system cache that involve a memory copy of the data from the cache to the application's buffer. The file system will not regain control until the copy operation is complete, even if the disk must be accessed to retrieve the page.

cacheSyncDataMapsPerSec.name: cacheSyncDataMapsPerSec
cacheSyncDataMapsPerSec.description: Sync Data Maps/sec counts the frequency that a file system, such as NTFS, maps a page of a file into the file system cache to read the page, and wishes to wait for the page to be retrieved if it is not in main memory.

cacheSyncFastReadsPerSec.name: cacheSyncFastReadsPerSec
cacheSyncFastReadsPerSec.description: Sync Fast Reads/sec is the frequency of reads from the file system cache that bypass the installed file system and retrieve the data directly from the cache. Normally, file I/O requests invoke the appropriate file system to retrieve data from a file, but this path permits direct retrieval of data from the cache without file system involvement if the data is in the cache. Even if the data is not in the cache, one invocation of the file system is avoided. If the data is not in the cache, the request (application program call) will wait until the data has been retrieved from disk.

cacheSyncMDLReadsPerSec.name: cacheSyncMDLReadsPerSec
cacheSyncMDLReadsPerSec.description: Sync MDL Reads/sec is the frequency of reads from the file system cache that use a Memory Descriptor List (MDL) to access the pages. The MDL contains the physical address of each page in the transfer, thus permitting Direct Memory Access (DMA) of the pages. If the accessed page(s) are not in main memory, the caller will wait for the pages to fault in from the disk.

cacheSyncPinReadsPerSec.name: cacheSyncPinReadsPerSec
cacheSyncPinReadsPerSec.description: Sync Pin Reads/sec is the frequency of reading data into the file system cache preparatory to writing the data back to disk. Pages read in this fashion are pinned in memory at the completion of the read. The file system will not regain control until the page is pinned in the file system cache, in particular if the disk must be accessed to retrieve the page. While pinned, a page's physical address in the file system cache will not be altered.

dhcpServer.name: dhcpServer
dhcpServer.description: The DHCP Server performance object provides counters for monitoring DHCP service activity. The DHCP service enables the server to perform as a DHCP server and configure DHCP-enabled client computers on your network as described in the DHCP standard. This object is available when the service is running. The following table describes the counters provided by the DHCP Server object and how to interpret the values when monitoring DHCP service performance.

dhcpSrvAcksPerSec.name: dhcpSrvAcksPerSec
dhcpSrvAcksPerSec.description: Rate of DHCP Acks sent by the DHCP server.

dhcpSrvActiveQueueLength.name: dhcpSrvActiveQueueLength
dhcpSrvActiveQueueLength.description: The Number of packets in the processing queue of the DHCP server.

dhcpSrvConflictCheckQueueLength.name: dhcpSrvConflictCheckQueueLength
dhcpSrvConflictCheckQueueLength.description: The Number of packets in the DHCP server queue waiting on conflict detection (ping).

dhcpSrvDeclinesPerSec.name: dhcpSrvDeclinesPerSec
dhcpSrvDeclinesPerSec.description: Rate of DHCP Declines received by the DHCP server.

dhcpSrvDiscoversPerSec.name: dhcpSrvDiscoversPerSec
dhcpSrvDiscoversPerSec.description: Rate of DHCP Discovers received by the DHCP server.

dhcpSrvDuplicatesDroppedPerSec.name: dhcpSrvDuplicatesDroppedPerSec
dhcpSrvDuplicatesDroppedPerSec.description: Duplicates Dropped/sec is the rate at which the DHCP server received duplicate packets.

dhcpSrvInformsPerSec.name: dhcpSrvInformsPerSec
dhcpSrvInformsPerSec.description: Rate of DHCP Informs received by the DHCP server.

dhcpSrvMillisecondsPerPacketAvg.name: dhcpSrvMillisecondsPerPacketAvg
dhcpSrvMillisecondsPerPacketAvg.description: The average time per packet taken by the DHCP server to send a response.

dhcpSrvNacksPerSec.name: dhcpSrvNacksPerSec
dhcpSrvNacksPerSec.description: Rate of DHCP Nacks sent by the DHCP server.

dhcpSrvOffersPerSec.name: dhcpSrvOffersPerSec
dhcpSrvOffersPerSec.description: Rate of DHCP Offers sent out by the DHCP server.

dhcpSrvPacketsExpiredPerSec.name: dhcpSrvPacketsExpiredPerSec
dhcpSrvPacketsExpiredPerSec.description: Packets Expired/sec is the rate at which packets get expired in the DHCP server message queue.

dhcpSrvPacketsReceivedPerSec.name: dhcpSrvPacketsReceivedPerSec
dhcpSrvPacketsReceivedPerSec.description: Packets Received/sec is the rate at which packets are received by the DHCP server.

dhcpSrvReleasesPerSec.name: dhcpSrvReleasesPerSec
dhcpSrvReleasesPerSec.description: Rate of DHCP Releases received by the DHCP server.

dhcpSrvRequestsPerSec.name: dhcpSrvRequestsPerSec
dhcpSrvRequestsPerSec.description: Rate of DHCP Requests received by the DHCP server.

distributeTransactionCoordinator.name: distributeTransactionCoordinator
distributeTransactionCoordinator.description: The Distributed Transaction Coordinator performance object provides statistics about Distributed Transaction Coordinator (MS DTC), part of Component Services (formerly known as Transaction Server) that coordinates external, or two-phase transactions. Among other things, MS DTC is used to coordinate two-phase transactions by Message Queuing.

dtcActiveTransactionsMaximum.name: dtcActiveTransactionsMaximum
dtcActiveTransactionsMaximum.description: Maximum number of transactions ever concurrently active

dtcForceAbortedTransactions.name: dtcForceAbortedTransactions
dtcForceAbortedTransactions.description: Number of transactions aborted by the system administrator

dtcForceCommittedTransactions.name: dtcForceCommittedTransactions
dtcForceCommittedTransactions.description: Number of transactions committed by the system administrator

dtcResponseTimeAverage.name: dtcResponseTimeAverage
dtcResponseTimeAverage.description: Average time delta between transaction begin and commit

dtcResponseTimeMaximum.name: dtcResponseTimeMaximum
dtcResponseTimeMaximum.description: Maximum time delta between transaction begin and commit

dtcResponseTimeMinimum.name: dtcResponseTimeMinimum
dtcResponseTimeMinimum.description: Minimum time delta between transaction begin and commit

dns.name: dns
dns.description: The DNS performance object provides counters for monitoring various areas of performance of the DNS service that enables client computers on your network to register and resolve DNS domain names. These names are used to find and access resources offered by other computers on your network or other networks, such as the Internet. The data reported by the DNS object includes the number of overall queries and responses processed by a DNS server, the number of DNS queries and responses processed using either the User Datagram Protocol (UDP) or the Transmission Control Protocol (TCP), the number of queries and responses that used recursion to look up and fully resolve DNS names on behalf of requesting clients, and the number of queries and responses made to servers using the WINS lookup integration features of the DNS service.

dnsAXFRRequestReceived.name: dnsAXFRRequestReceived
dnsAXFRRequestReceived.description: AXFR Request Received is the total number of full zone transfer requests received by the master DNS server.

dnsAXFRRequestSent.name: dnsAXFRRequestSent
dnsAXFRRequestSent.description: AXFR Request Sent is the total number of full zone transfer requests sent by the secondary DNS server.

dnsAXFRResponseReceived.name: dnsAXFRResponseReceived
dnsAXFRResponseReceived.description: AXFR Response Received is the total number of full zone transfer responses received by the secondary DNS server.

dnsAXFRSuccessReceived.name: dnsAXFRSuccessReceived
dnsAXFRSuccessReceived.description: AXFR Success Received is the total number of successful full zone transfers received by the secondary DNS server.

dnsAXFRSuccessSent.name: dnsAXFRSuccessSent
dnsAXFRSuccessSent.description: AXFR Success Sent is the total number of successful full zone transfers of the master DNS server.

dnsCachingMemory.name: dnsCachingMemory
dnsCachingMemory.description: Caching Memory is the total caching memory used by DNS server.

dnsDatabaseNodeMemory.name: dnsDatabaseNodeMemory
dnsDatabaseNodeMemory.description: Database Node Memory is the total database node memory used by DNS server.

dnsDynamicUpdateNoOperation.name: dnsDynamicUpdateNoOperation
dnsDynamicUpdateNoOperation.description: Dynamic Update NoOperation is the total number of No-operation/Empty dynamic update requests received by the DNS server.

dnsDynamicUpdateNoOpPerSec.name: dnsDynamicUpdateNoOpPerSec
dnsDynamicUpdateNoOpPerSec.description: Dynamic Update NoOperation/sec is the average number of No-operation/Empty dynamic update requests received by the DNS server in each second.

dnsDynamicUpdateQueued.name: dnsDynamicUpdateQueued
dnsDynamicUpdateQueued.description: Dynamic Update Queued is the total number of dynamic updates queued by the DNS server.

dnsDynamicUpdateReceived.name: dnsDynamicUpdateReceived
dnsDynamicUpdateReceived.description: Dynamic Update Received is the total number of dynamic update requests received by the DNS server.

dnsDynamicUpdateReceivedPerSec.name: dnsDynamicUpdateReceivedPerSec
dnsDynamicUpdateReceivedPerSec.description: Dynamic Update Received/sec is the average number of dynamic update requests received by the DNS server in each second.

dnsDynamicUpdateRejected.name: dnsDynamicUpdateRejected
dnsDynamicUpdateRejected.description: Dynamic Update Rejected is the total number of dynamic updates rejected by the DNS server.

dnsDynamicUpdateTimeOuts.name: dnsDynamicUpdateTimeOuts
dnsDynamicUpdateTimeOuts.description: Dynamic Update TimeOuts is the total number of dynamic update timeouts of the DNS server.

dnsDynamicUpdateWriteToDB.name: dnsDynamicUpdateWriteToDB
dnsDynamicUpdateWriteToDB.description: Dynamic Update Written to Database is the total number of dynamic updates written to the database by the DNS server.

dnsDynamicUpdateWriteToDBPerSec.name: dnsDynamicUpdateWriteToDBPerSec
dnsDynamicUpdateWriteToDBPerSec.description: Dynamic Update Written to Database/sec is the average number of dynamic updates written to the database by the DNS server in each second.

dnsIXFRRequestReceived.name: dnsIXFRRequestReceived
dnsIXFRRequestReceived.description: IXFR Request Received is the total number of incremental zone transfer requests received by the master DNS server.

dnsIXFRRequestSent.name: dnsIXFRRequestSent
dnsIXFRRequestSent.description: IXFR Request Sent is the total number of incremental zone transfer requests sent by the secondary DNS server.

dnsIXFRResponseReceived.name: dnsIXFRResponseReceived
dnsIXFRResponseReceived.description: IXFR Response Received is the total number of incrementalzone transfer responses received by the secondary DNS server.

dnsIXFRSuccessReceived.name: dnsIXFRSuccessReceived
dnsIXFRSuccessReceived.description: IXFR Success Received is the total number of successful incremental zone transfers received by the secondary DNS server.

dnsIXFRSuccessSent.name: dnsIXFRSuccessSent
dnsIXFRSuccessSent.description: IXFR Success Sent is the total number of successful incremental zone transfers of the master DNS server.

dnsIXFRTCPSuccessReceived.name: dnsIXFRTCPSuccessReceived
dnsIXFRTCPSuccessReceived.description: IXFR TCP Success Received is the total number of successful TCP incremental zone transfers received by the secondary DNS server.

dnsIXFRUDPSuccessReceived.name: dnsIXFRUDPSuccessReceived
dnsIXFRUDPSuccessReceived.description: IXFR UDP Success Received is the total number of successful UDP incremental zone transfers received by the secondary DNS server.

dnsNbstatMemory.name: dnsNbstatMemory
dnsNbstatMemory.description: Nbstat Memory is the total Nbstat memory used by DNS server.

dnsNotifyReceived.name: dnsNotifyReceived
dnsNotifyReceived.description: Notify Received is the total number of notifies received by the secondary DNS server.

dnsNotifySent.name: dnsNotifySent
dnsNotifySent.description: Notify Sent is the total number of notifies sent by the master DNS server.

dnsRecordFlowMemory.name: dnsRecordFlowMemory
dnsRecordFlowMemory.description: Record Flow Memory is the total record flow memory used by DNS server.

dnsRecursiveQueries.name: dnsRecursiveQueries
dnsRecursiveQueries.description: Recursive Queries is the total number of recursive queries received by DNS server.

dnsRecursiveQueriesPerSec.name: dnsRecursiveQueriesPerSec
dnsRecursiveQueriesPerSec.description: Recursive Queries/sec is the average number of recursive queries received by DNS server in each sencond.

dnsRecursiveQueryFailure.name: dnsRecursiveQueryFailure
dnsRecursiveQueryFailure.description: Recursive Query Failure is the total number of recursive query failures.

dnsRecursiveQueryFailurePerSec.name: dnsRecursiveQueryFailurePerSec
dnsRecursiveQueryFailurePerSec.description: Recursive Query Failure/sec is the average number of recursive query failures in each second.

dnsRecursiveSendTimeOuts.name: dnsRecursiveSendTimeOuts
dnsRecursiveSendTimeOuts.description: Recursive TimeOuts is the total number of recursive query sending timeouts.

dnsRecursiveTimeOutPerSec.name: dnsRecursiveTimeOutPerSec
dnsRecursiveTimeOutPerSec.description: Recursive TimeOut/sec is the average number of recursive query sending timeouts in each second.

dnsSecureUpdateFailure.name: dnsSecureUpdateFailure
dnsSecureUpdateFailure.description: Secure Update Failure is the total number of secure updates failed of the DNS server.

dnsSecureUpdateReceived.name: dnsSecureUpdateReceived
dnsSecureUpdateReceived.description: Secure Update Received is the total number of secure update requests received by the DNS server.

dnsSecureUpdateReceivedPerSec.name: dnsSecureUpdateReceivedPerSec
dnsSecureUpdateReceivedPerSec.description: Secure Update Received/sec is the average number of secure update requests received by the DNS server in each second.

dnsTCPMessageMemory.name: dnsTCPMessageMemory
dnsTCPMessageMemory.description: TCP Message Memory is the total TCP message memory used by DNS server.

dnsTCPQueryReceived.name: dnsTCPQueryReceived
dnsTCPQueryReceived.description: TCP Query Received is the total number of TCP queries received by DNS server.

dnsTCPQueryReceivedPerSec.name: dnsTCPQueryReceivedPerSec
dnsTCPQueryReceivedPerSec.description: TCP Query Received/sec is the average number of TCP queries received by DNS server in each second.

dnsTCPResponseSent.name: dnsTCPResponseSent
dnsTCPResponseSent.description: TCP Response Sent is the total number of TCP reponses sent by DNS server.

dnsTCPResponseSentPerSec.name: dnsTCPResponseSentPerSec
dnsTCPResponseSentPerSec.description: TCP Response Sent/sec is the average number of TCP reponses sent by DNS server in each second.

dnsTotalQueryReceived.name: dnsTotalQueryReceived
dnsTotalQueryReceived.description: Total Query Received is the total number of queries received by DNS server.

dnsTotalQueryReceivedPerSec.name: dnsTotalQueryReceivedPerSec
dnsTotalQueryReceivedPerSec.description: Total Query Received/sec is the average number of queries received by DNS server in each second.

dnsTotalResponseSent.name: dnsTotalResponseSent
dnsTotalResponseSent.description: Total Response Sent is the total number of reponses sent by DNS server.

dnsTotalResponseSentPerSec.name: dnsTotalResponseSentPerSec
dnsTotalResponseSentPerSec.description: Total Response Sent/sec is the average number of reponses sent by DNS server in each second.

dnsUDPMessageMemory.name: dnsUDPMessageMemory
dnsUDPMessageMemory.description: UDP Message Memory is the total UDP message memory used by DNS server.

dnsUDPQueryReceived.name: dnsUDPQueryReceived
dnsUDPQueryReceived.description: UDP Query Received is the total number of UDP queries received by DNS server.

dnsUDPQueryReceivedPerSec.name: dnsUDPQueryReceivedPerSec
dnsUDPQueryReceivedPerSec.description: UDP Query Received/sec is the average number of UDP queries received by DNS server in each second.

dnsUDPResponseSent.name: dnsUDPResponseSent
dnsUDPResponseSent.description: UDP Response Sent is the total number of UDP reponses sent by DNS server.

dnsUDPResponseSentPerSec.name: dnsUDPResponseSentPerSec
dnsUDPResponseSentPerSec.description: UDP Response Sent/sec is the average number of UDP reponses sent by DNS server in each second.

dnsWINSLookupReceived.name: dnsWINSLookupReceived
dnsWINSLookupReceived.description: WINS Lookup Received is the total number of WINS lookup requests received by the server.

dnsWINSLookupReceivedPerSec.name: dnsWINSLookupReceivedPerSec
dnsWINSLookupReceivedPerSec.description: WINS Lookup Received/sec is the average number of WINS lookup requests received by the server in each second.

dnsWINSResponseSent.name: dnsWINSResponseSent
dnsWINSResponseSent.description: WINS Response Sent is the total number of WINS lookup responses sent by the server.

dnsWINSResponseSentPerSec.name: dnsWINSResponseSentPerSec
dnsWINSResponseSentPerSec.description: WINS Response Sent/sec is the average number of WINS lookup responses sent by the server in each second.

dnsWINSReverseLookupReceived.name: dnsWINSReverseLookupReceived
dnsWINSReverseLookupReceived.description: WINS Reverse Lookup Received is the total number of WINS reverse lookup requests received by the server.

dnsWINSReverseLookupRcvPerSec.name: dnsWINSReverseLookupRcvPerSec
dnsWINSReverseLookupRcvPerSec.description: WINS Reverse Lookup Received/sec is the average number of WINS reverse lookup requests received by the server in each second.

dnsWINSReverseResponseSent.name: dnsWINSReverseResponseSent
dnsWINSReverseResponseSent.description: WINS Reverse Response Sent is the total number of WINS Reverse lookup responses sent by the server.

dnsWINSReverseResponseSentPerSec.name: dnsWINSReverseResponseSentPerSec
dnsWINSReverseResponseSentPerSec.description: WINS Reverse Response Sent/sec is the average number of WINS Reverse lookup responses sent by the server in each second.

dnsZoneTransferFailure.name: dnsZoneTransferFailure
dnsZoneTransferFailure.description: Zone Transfer Failure is the total number of failed zone transfers of the master DNS server.

dnsZoneTransferRequestReceived.name: dnsZoneTransferRequestReceived
dnsZoneTransferRequestReceived.description: Zone Transfer Request Received is the total number of zone transfer requests received by the master DNS server.

dnsZoneTransferSOARequestSent.name: dnsZoneTransferSOARequestSent
dnsZoneTransferSOARequestSent.description: Zone Transfer SOA Request Sent is the total number of zone transfer SOA requests sent by the secondary DNS server.

dnsZoneTransferSuccess.name: dnsZoneTransferSuccess
dnsZoneTransferSuccess.description: Zone Transfer Success is the total number of successful zone transfers of the master DNS server.

dotNETCLRDataTable.name: dotNETCLRDataTable
dotNETCLRDataTable.description: The Performance console .NET CLR Data category includes counters that provide information about the exceptions thrown by an application.

dotNETCLRDataEntry.name: dotNETCLRDataEntry
dotNETCLRDataEntry.description: Performance information for one particular instance of '.NET CLR Data' object.

ncdSQLClntCurNumConnPools.name: ncdSQLClntCurNumConnPools
ncdSQLClntCurNumConnPools.description: Current number of pools associated with the process.

ncdSQLClntCurNumConns.name: ncdSQLClntCurNumConns
ncdSQLClntCurNumConns.description: Current number of connections, pooled or not.

ncdSQLClntCurNumPoolConns.name: ncdSQLClntCurNumPoolConns
ncdSQLClntCurNumPoolConns.description: Current number of connections in all pools associated with the process.

ncdSQLClntPeakNumPoolConns.name: ncdSQLClntPeakNumPoolConns
ncdSQLClntPeakNumPoolConns.description: The highest number of connections in all pools since the process started.

ncdSQLClntTotalNumFailedCommands.name: ncdSQLClntTotalNumFailedCommands
ncdSQLClntTotalNumFailedCommands.description: The total number of command executes that have failed for any reason.

ncdSQLClntTotalNumFailedConnects.name: ncdSQLClntTotalNumFailedConnects
ncdSQLClntTotalNumFailedConnects.description: The total number of connection open attempts that have failed for any reason.

dotNETCLRExceptionsTable.name: dotNETCLRExceptionsTable
dotNETCLRExceptionsTable.description: The Performance console .NET CLR Exceptions category includes counters that provide information about the exceptions thrown by an application.

dotNETCLRExceptionsEntry.name: dotNETCLRExceptionsEntry
dotNETCLRExceptionsEntry.description: Performance information for one particular instance of '.NET CLR Exceptions' object.

nceNumOfExcepsThrown.name: nceNumOfExcepsThrown
nceNumOfExcepsThrown.description: This counter displays the total number of exceptions thrown since the start of the application. These include both .NET exceptions and unmanaged exceptions that get converted into .NET exceptions e.g. null pointer reference exception in unmanaged code would get re-thrown in managed code as a .NET System.NullReferenceException; this counter includes both handled and unhandled exceptions. Exceptions that are re-thrown would get counted again. Exceptions should only occur in rare situations and not in the normal control flow of the program.

nceNumOfExcepsThrownPerSec.name: nceNumOfExcepsThrownPerSec
nceNumOfExcepsThrownPerSec.description: This counter displays the number of exceptions thrown per second. These include both .NET exceptions and unmanaged exceptions that get converted into .NET exceptions e.g. null pointer reference exception in unmanaged code would get re-thrown in managed code as a .NET System.NullReferenceException; this counter includes both handled and unhandled exceptions. Exceptions should only occur in rare situations and not in the normal control flow of the program; this counter was designed as an indicator of potential performance problems due to large (>100s) rate of exceptions thrown. This counter is not an average over time; it displays the difference between the values observed in the last two samples divided by the duration of the sample interval.

nceNumOfFiltersPerSec.name: nceNumOfFiltersPerSec
nceNumOfFiltersPerSec.description: This counter displays the number of .NET exception filters executed per second. An exception filter evaluates whether an exception should be handled or not. This counter tracks the rate of exception filters evaluated; irrespective of whether the exception was handled or not. This counter is not an average over time; it displays the difference between the values observed in the last two samples divided by the duration of the sample interval.

nceNumOfFinallysPerSec.name: nceNumOfFinallysPerSec
nceNumOfFinallysPerSec.description: This counter displays the number of finally blocks executed per second. A finally block is guaranteed to be executed regardless of how the try block was exited. Only the finally blocks that are executed for an exception are counted; finally blocks on normal code paths are not counted by this counter. This counter is not an average over time; it displays the difference between the values observed in the last two samples divided by the duration of the sample interval.

nceThrowToCatchDepthPerSec.name: nceThrowToCatchDepthPerSec
nceThrowToCatchDepthPerSec.description: This counter displays the number of stack frames traversed from the frame that threw the .NET exception to the frame that handled the exception per second. This counter resets to 0 when an exception handler is entered; so nested exceptions would show the handler to handler stack depth. This counter is not an average over time; it displays the difference between the values observed in the last two samples divided by the duration of the sample interval.

dotNETCLRInteropTable.name: dotNETCLRInteropTable
dotNETCLRInteropTable.description: The Performance console .NET CLR Interop category includes counters that provide information about an application's interaction with COM components, COM+ services, and external type libraries.

dotNETCLRInteropEntry.name: dotNETCLRInteropEntry
dotNETCLRInteropEntry.description: Performance information for one particular instance of '.NET CLR Interop' object.

nciNumOfCCWs.name: nciNumOfCCWs
nciNumOfCCWs.description: This counter displays the current number of Com-Callable-Wrappers (CCWs). A CCW is a proxy for the .NET managed object being referenced from unmanaged COM client(s). This counter was designed to indicate the number of managed objects being referenced by unmanaged COM code.

nciNumOfStubs.name: nciNumOfStubs
nciNumOfStubs.description: This counter displays the current number of stubs created by the CLR. Stubs are responsible for marshalling arguments and return values from managed to unmanaged code and vice versa; during a COM Interop call or PInvoke call.

nciNumOfMarshalling.name: nciNumOfMarshalling
nciNumOfMarshalling.description: This counter displays the total number of times arguments and return values have been marshaled from managed to unmanaged code and vice versa since the start of the application. This counter is not incremented if the stubs are inlined. (Stubs are responsible for marshalling arguments and return values). Stubs usually get inlined if the marshalling overhead is small.

dotNETCLRJitTable.name: dotNETCLRJitTable
dotNETCLRJitTable.description: The Performance console .NET CLR JIT category includes counters that provide information about code that has been JIT-compiled.

dotNETCLRJitEntry.name: dotNETCLRJitEntry
dotNETCLRJitEntry.description: Performance information for one particular instance of '.NET CLR Jit' object.

ncjNumOfILBytesJitted.name: ncjNumOfILBytesJitted
ncjNumOfILBytesJitted.description: This counter displays the total IL bytes jitted since the start of the application. This counter is exactly equivalent to the 'Total # of IL Bytes Jitted' counter.

ncjNumOfMethodsJitted.name: ncjNumOfMethodsJitted
ncjNumOfMethodsJitted.description: This counter displays the total number of methods compiled Just-In-Time (JIT) by the CLR JIT compiler since the start of the application. This counter does not include the pre-jitted methods.

ncjPercentTimeInJit.name: ncjPercentTimeInJit
ncjPercentTimeInJit.description: This counter displays the percentage of elapsed time spent in JIT compilation since the last JIT compilation phase. This counter is updated at the end of every JIT compilation phase. A JIT compilation phase is the phase when a method and its dependencies are being compiled.

ncjILBytesJittedPerSec.name: ncjILBytesJittedPerSec
ncjILBytesJittedPerSec.description: This counter displays the rate at which IL bytes are jitted per second. This counter is not an average over time; it displays the difference between the values observed in the last two samples divided by the duration of the sample interval.

ncjStandardJitFailures.name: ncjStandardJitFailures
ncjStandardJitFailures.description: This counter displays the peak number of methods the JIT compiler has failed to JIT since the start of the application. This failure can occur if the IL cannot be verified or if there was an internal error in the JIT compiler.

ncjTotalNumOfILBytesJitted.name: ncjTotalNumOfILBytesJitted
ncjTotalNumOfILBytesJitted.description: This counter displays the total IL bytes jitted since the start of the application. This counter is exactly equivalent to the '# of IL Bytes Jitted' counter.

dotNETCLRLoadingTable.name: dotNETCLRLoadingTable
dotNETCLRLoadingTable.description: The Performance console .NET CLR Loading category includes counters that provide information about assemblies, classes, and application domains that are loaded.

dotNETCLRLoadingEntry.name: dotNETCLRLoadingEntry
dotNETCLRLoadingEntry.description: Performance information for one particular instance of '.NET CLR Loading' object.

nclBytesInLoaderHeap.name: nclBytesInLoaderHeap
nclBytesInLoaderHeap.description: This counter displays the current size (in bytes) of the memory committed by the class loader across all AppDomains. (Committed memory is the physical memory for which space has been reserved on the disk paging file.)

nclCurrentAssemblies.name: nclCurrentAssemblies
nclCurrentAssemblies.description: This counter displays the current number of Assemblies loaded across all AppDomains in this application. If the Assembly is loaded as domain-neutral from multiple AppDomains then this counter is incremented once only. Assemblies can be loaded as domain-neutral when their code can be shared by all AppDomains or they can be loaded as domain-specific when their code is private to the AppDomain.

nclCurrentClassesLoaded.name: nclCurrentClassesLoaded
nclCurrentClassesLoaded.description: This counter displays the current number of classes loaded in all Assemblies.

nclCurrentAppdomains.name: nclCurrentAppdomains
nclCurrentAppdomains.description: This counter displays the current number of AppDomains loaded in this application. AppDomains (application domains) provide a secure and versatile unit of processing that the CLR can use to provide isolation between applications running in the same process.

nclRateOfAssemblies.name: nclRateOfAssemblies
nclRateOfAssemblies.description: This counter displays the number of Assemblies loaded across all AppDomains per second. If the Assembly is loaded as domain-neutral from multiple AppDomains then this counter is incremented once only. Assemblies can be loaded as domain-neutral when their code can be shared by all AppDomains or they can be loaded as domain-specific when their code is private to the AppDomain. This counter is not an average over time; it displays the difference between the values observed in the last two samples divided by the duration of the sample interval.

nclRateOfClassesLoaded.name: nclRateOfClassesLoaded
nclRateOfClassesLoaded.description: This counter displays the number of classes loaded per second in all Assemblies. This counter is not an average over time; it displays the difference between the values observed in the last two samples divided by the duration of the sample interval.

nclRateOfLoadFailures.name: nclRateOfLoadFailures
nclRateOfLoadFailures.description: This counter displays the number of classes that failed to load per second. This counter is not an average over time; it displays the difference between the values observed in the last two samples divided by the duration of the sample interval. These load failures could be due to many reasons like inadequate security or illegal format. Full details can be found in the profiling services help.

nclRateOfAppdomains.name: nclRateOfAppdomains
nclRateOfAppdomains.description: This counter displays the number of AppDomains loaded per second. AppDomains (application domains) provide a secure and versatile unit of processing that the CLR can use to provide isolation between applications running in the same process. This counter is not an average over time; it displays the difference between the values observed in the last two samples divided by the duration of the sample interval.

nclRateOfAppdomainsUnloaded.name: nclRateOfAppdomainsUnloaded
nclRateOfAppdomainsUnloaded.description: This counter displays the number of AppDomains unloaded per second. This counter is not an average over time; it displays the difference between the values observed in the last two samples divided by the duration of the sample interval.

nclTotalNumOfLoadFailures.name: nclTotalNumOfLoadFailures
nclTotalNumOfLoadFailures.description: This counter displays the peak number of classes that have failed to load since the start of the application. These load failures could be due to many reasons like inadequate security or illegal format. Full details can be found in the profiling services help.

nclTotalAppdomains.name: nclTotalAppdomains
nclTotalAppdomains.description: This counter displays the peak number of AppDomains loaded since the start of this application. AppDomains (application domains) provide a secure and versatile unit of processing that the CLR can use to provide isolation between applications running in the same process.

nclTotalAssemblies.name: nclTotalAssemblies
nclTotalAssemblies.description: This counter displays the total number of Assemblies loaded since the start of this application. If the Assembly is loaded as domain-neutral from multiple AppDomains then this counter is incremented once only. Assemblies can be loaded as domain-neutral when their code can be shared by all AppDomains or they can be loaded as domain-specific when their code is private to the AppDomain.

nclTotalClassesLoaded.name: nclTotalClassesLoaded
nclTotalClassesLoaded.description: This counter displays the cumulative number of classes loaded in all Assemblies since the start of this application.

nclTotalAppdomainsUnloaded.name: nclTotalAppdomainsUnloaded
nclTotalAppdomainsUnloaded.description: This counter displays the total number of AppDomains unloaded since the start of the application. If an AppDomain is loaded and unloaded multiple times this counter would count each of those unloads as separate.

dotNETCLRLocksAndThreadsTable.name: dotNETCLRLocksAndThreadsTable
dotNETCLRLocksAndThreadsTable.description: The Performance console .NET CLR LocksAndThreads category includes counters that provide information about managed locks and threads that an application uses.

dotNETCLRLocksAndThreadsEntry.name: dotNETCLRLocksAndThreadsEntry
dotNETCLRLocksAndThreadsEntry.description: Performance information for one particular instance of '.NET CLR LocksAndThreads' object.

ncltNumOfCurrentLogicalThread.name: ncltNumOfCurrentLogicalThread
ncltNumOfCurrentLogicalThread.description: This counter displays the number of current .NET thread objects in the application. A .NET thread object is created either by new System.Threading.Thread or when an unmanaged thread enters the managed environment. This counters maintains the count of both running and stopped threads. This counter is not an average over time; it just displays the last observed value.

ncltNumOfCurrentPhysicalThread.name: ncltNumOfCurrentPhysicalThread
ncltNumOfCurrentPhysicalThread.description: This counter displays the number of native OS threads created and owned by the CLR to act as underlying threads for .NET thread objects. This counters value does not include the threads used by the CLR in its internal operations; it is a subset of the threads in the OS process.

ncltNumOfCurrentRecognizedThread.name: ncltNumOfCurrentRecognizedThread
ncltNumOfCurrentRecognizedThread.description: This counter displays the number of threads that are currently recognized by the CLR; they have a corresponding .NET thread object associated with them. These threads are not created by the CLR; they are created outside the CLR but have since run inside the CLR at least once. Only unique threads are tracked; threads with same thread ID re-entering the CLR or recreated after thread exit are not counted twice.

ncltNumOfTotalRecognizedThread.name: ncltNumOfTotalRecognizedThread
ncltNumOfTotalRecognizedThread.description: This counter displays the total number of threads that have been recognized by the CLR since the start of this application; these threads have a corresponding .NET thread object associated with them. These threads are not created by the CLR; they are created outside the CLR but have since run inside the CLR at least once. Only unique threads are tracked; threads with same thread ID re-entering the CLR or recreated after thread exit are not counted twice.

ncltContentionRatePerSec.name: ncltContentionRatePerSec
ncltContentionRatePerSec.description: Rate at which threads in the runtime attempt to acquire a managed lock unsuccessfully. Managed locks can be acquired in many ways; by the 'lock' statement in C# or by calling System.Monitor.Enter or by using MethodImplOptions.Synchronized custom attribute.

ncltCurrentQueueLength.name: ncltCurrentQueueLength
ncltCurrentQueueLength.description: This counter displays the total number of threads currently waiting to acquire some managed lock in the application. This counter is not an average over time; it displays the last observed value.

ncltQueueLengthPerSec.name: ncltQueueLengthPerSec
ncltQueueLengthPerSec.description: This counter displays the number of threads per second waiting to acquire some lock in the application. This counter is not an average over time; it displays the difference between the values observed in the last two samples divided by the duration of the sample interval.

ncltQueueLengthPeak.name: ncltQueueLengthPeak
ncltQueueLengthPeak.description: This counter displays the total number of threads that waited to acquire some managed lock since the start of the application.

ncltTotalNumOfContentions.name: ncltTotalNumOfContentions
ncltTotalNumOfContentions.description: This counter displays the total number of times threads in the CLR have attempted to acquire a managed lock unsuccessfully. Managed locks can be acquired in many ways; by the 'lock' statement in C# or by calling System.Monitor.Enter or by using MethodImplOptions.Synchronized custom attribute.

ncltRateOfRecognizedThreadPerSec.name: ncltRateOfRecognizedThreadPerSec
ncltRateOfRecognizedThreadPerSec.description: This counter displays the number of threads per second that have been recognized by the CLR; these threads have a corresponding .NET thread object associated with them. These threads are not created by the CLR; they are created outside the CLR but have since run inside the CLR at least once. Only unique threads are tracked; threads with same thread ID re-entering the CLR or recreated after thread exit are not counted twice. This counter is not an average over time; it displays the difference between the values observed in the last two samples divided by the duration of the sample interval.

dotNETCLRMemoryTable.name: dotNETCLRMemoryTable
dotNETCLRMemoryTable.description: The Performance console .NET CLR Memory category includes counters that provide information about the garbage collector.

dotNETCLRMemoryEntry.name: dotNETCLRMemoryEntry
dotNETCLRMemoryEntry.description: Performance information for one particular instance of '.NET CLR Memory' object.

ncmNumBytesInAllHeaps.name: ncmNumBytesInAllHeaps
ncmNumBytesInAllHeaps.description: This counter is the sum of four other counters; Gen 0 Heap Size; Gen 1 Heap Size; Gen 2 Heap Size and the Large Object Heap Size. This counter indicates the current memory allocated in bytes on the GC Heaps.

ncmNumGCHandles.name: ncmNumGCHandles
ncmNumGCHandles.description: This counter displays the current number of GC Handles in use. GCHandles are handles to resources external to the CLR and the managed environment. Handles occupy small amounts of memory in the GCHeap but potentially expensive unmanaged resources.

ncmNumGen0Collections.name: ncmNumGen0Collections
ncmNumGen0Collections.description: This counter displays the number of times the generation 0 objects (youngest; most recently allocated) are garbage collected (Gen 0 GC) since the start of the application. Gen 0 GC occurs when the available memory in generation 0 is not sufficient to satisfy an allocation request. This counter is incremented at the end of a Gen 0 GC. Higher generation GCs include all lower generation GCs. This counter is explicitly incremented when a higher generation (Gen 1 or Gen 2) GC occurs. _Global_ counter value is not accurate and should be ignored. This counter displays the last observed value.

ncmNumGen1Collections.name: ncmNumGen1Collections
ncmNumGen1Collections.description: This counter displays the number of times the generation 1 objects are garbage collected since the start of the application. The counter is incremented at the end of a Gen 1 GC. Higher generation GCs include all lower generation GCs. This counter is explicitly incremented when a higher generation (Gen 2) GC occurs. _Global_ counter value is not accurate and should be ignored. This counter displays the last observed value.

ncmNumGen2Collections.name: ncmNumGen2Collections
ncmNumGen2Collections.description: This counter displays the number of times the generation 2 objects (older) are garbage collected since the start of the application. The counter is incremented at the end of a Gen 2 GC (also called full GC). _Global_ counter value is not accurate and should be ignored. This counter displays the last observed value.

ncmNumInducedGC.name: ncmNumInducedGC
ncmNumInducedGC.description: This counter displays the peak number of times a garbage collection was performed because of an explicit call to GC.Collect. Its a good practice to let the GC tune the frequency of its collections.

ncmNumTotalCommittedBytes.name: ncmNumTotalCommittedBytes
ncmNumTotalCommittedBytes.description: This counter displays the amount of virtual memory (in bytes) currently committed by the Garbage Collector. (Committed memory is the physical memory for which space has been reserved on the disk paging file).

ncmNumTotalReservedBytes.name: ncmNumTotalReservedBytes
ncmNumTotalReservedBytes.description: This counter displays the amount of virtual memory (in bytes) currently reserved by the Garbage Collector. (Reserved memory is the virtual memory space reserved for the application but no disk or main memory pages have been used.)

ncmNumOfPinnedObjects.name: ncmNumOfPinnedObjects
ncmNumOfPinnedObjects.description: This counter displays the number of pinned objects encountered in the last GC. This counter tracks the pinned objects only in the heaps that were garbage collected e.g. a Gen 0 GC would cause enumeration of pinned objects in the generation 0 heap only. A pinned object is one that the Garbage Collector cannot move in memory.

ncmNumOfSinkBlocksInUse.name: ncmNumOfSinkBlocksInUse
ncmNumOfSinkBlocksInUse.description: This counter displays the current number of sync blocks in use. Sync blocks are per-object data structures allocated for storing synchronization information. Sync blocks hold weak references to managed objects and need to be scanned by the Garbage Collector. Sync blocks are not limited to storing synchronization information and can also store COM interop metadata. This counter was designed to indicate performance problems with heavy use of synchronization primitives.

ncmPercentTimeInGC.name: ncmPercentTimeInGC
ncmPercentTimeInGC.description: % Time in GC is the percentage of elapsed time that was spent in performing a garbage collection (GC) since the last GC cycle. This counter is usually an indicator of the work done by the Garbage Collector on behalf of the application to collect and compact memory. This counter is updated only at the end of every GC and the counter value reflects the last observed value; its not an average.

ncmAllocatedBytesPerSec.name: ncmAllocatedBytesPerSec
ncmAllocatedBytesPerSec.description: This counter displays the rate of bytes per second allocated on the GC Heap. This counter is updated at the end of every GC; not at each allocation. This counter is not an average over time; it displays the difference between the values observed in the last two samples divided by the duration of the sample interval.

ncmFinalizationSurvivors.name: ncmFinalizationSurvivors
ncmFinalizationSurvivors.description: This counter displays the number of garbage collected objects that survive a collection because they are waiting to be finalized. If these objects hold references to other objects then those objects also survive but are not counted by this counter; the 'Promoted Finalization-Memory from Gen 0' and 'Promoted Finalization-Memory from Gen 1' counters represent all the memory that survived due to finalization. This counter is not a cumulative counter; its updated at the end of every GC with count of the survivors during that particular GC only. This counter was designed to indicate the extra overhead that the application might incur because of finalization.

ncmGen0PromotedBytesPerSec.name: ncmGen0PromotedBytesPerSec
ncmGen0PromotedBytesPerSec.description: This counter displays the bytes per second that are promoted from generation 0 (youngest) to generation 1; objects that are promoted just because they are waiting to be finalized are not included in this counter. Memory is promoted when it survives a garbage collection. This counter was designed as an indicator of relatively long-lived objects being created per sec. This counter displays the difference between the values observed in the last two samples divided by the duration of the sample interval.

ncmGen0HeapSize.name: ncmGen0HeapSize
ncmGen0HeapSize.description: This counter displays the maximum bytes that can be allocated in generation 0 (Gen 0); its does not indicate the current number of bytes allocated in Gen 0. A Gen 0 GC is triggered when the allocations since the last GC exceed this size. The Gen 0 size is tuned by the Garbage Collector and can change during the execution of the application. At the end of a Gen 0 collection the size of the Gen 0 heap is infact 0 bytes; this counter displays the size (in bytes) of allocations that would trigger the next Gen 0 GC. This counter is updated at the end of a GC; its not updated on every allocation.

ncmGen1PromotedBytesPerSec.name: ncmGen1PromotedBytesPerSec
ncmGen1PromotedBytesPerSec.description: This counter displays the bytes per second that are promoted from generation 1 to generation 2 (oldest); objects that are promoted just because they are waiting to be finalized are not included in this counter. Memory is promoted when it survives a garbage collection. Nothing is promoted from generation 2 since it is the oldest. This counter was designed as an indicator of very long-lived objects being created per sec. This counter displays the difference between the values observed in the last two samples divided by the duration of the sample interval.

ncmGen1HeapSize.name: ncmGen1HeapSize
ncmGen1HeapSize.description: This counter displays the current number of bytes in generation 1 (Gen 1); this counter does not display the maximum size of Gen 1. Objects are not directly allocated in this generation; they are promoted from previous Gen 0 GCs. This counter is updated at the end of a GC; its not updated on every allocation.

ncmGen2HeapSize.name: ncmGen2HeapSize
ncmGen2HeapSize.description: This counter displays the current number of bytes in generation 2 (Gen 2). Objects are not directly allocated in this generation; they are promoted from Gen 1 during previous Gen 1 GCs. This counter is updated at the end of a GC; its not updated on every allocation.

ncmLargeObjectHeapSize.name: ncmLargeObjectHeapSize
ncmLargeObjectHeapSize.description: This counter displays the current size of the Large Object Heap in bytes. Objects greater than 20 KBytes are treated as large objects by the Garbage Collector and are directly allocated in a special heap; they are not promoted through the generations. This counter is updated at the end of a GC; its not updated on every allocation.

ncmPromotFinalizationMemoryGen0.name: ncmPromotFinalizationMemoryGen0
ncmPromotFinalizationMemoryGen0.description: This counter displays the bytes of memory that are promoted from generation 0 to generation 1 just because they are waiting to be finalized. This counter displays the value observed at the end of the last GC; its not a cumulative counter.

ncmPromotFinalizationMemoryGen1.name: ncmPromotFinalizationMemoryGen1
ncmPromotFinalizationMemoryGen1.description: This counter displays the bytes of memory that are promoted from generation 1 to generation 2 just because they are waiting to be finalized. This counter displays the value observed at the end of the last GC; its not a cumulative counter. This counter is reset to 0 if the last GC was a Gen 0 GC only.

ncmPromotedMemoryFromGen0.name: ncmPromotedMemoryFromGen0
ncmPromotedMemoryFromGen0.description: This counter displays the bytes of memory that survive garbage collection (GC) and are promoted from generation 0 to generation 1; objects that are promoted just because they are waiting to be finalized are not included in this counter. This counter displays the value observed at the end of the last GC; its not a cumulative counter.

ncmPromotedMemoryFromGen1.name: ncmPromotedMemoryFromGen1
ncmPromotedMemoryFromGen1.description: This counter displays the bytes of memory that survive garbage collection (GC) and are promoted from generation 1 to generation 2; objects that are promoted just because they are waiting to be finalized are not included in this counter. This counter displays the value observed at the end of the last GC; its not a cumulative counter. This counter is reset to 0 if the last GC was a Gen 0 GC only.

ncmProcessID.name: ncmProcessID
ncmProcessID.description: This counter displays the process ID of the CLR process instance being monitored.

dotNETCLRNetworkingTable.name: dotNETCLRNetworkingTable
dotNETCLRNetworkingTable.description: The Performance console .NET CLR Networking category includes counters that provide information about data that an application sends and receives over the network.

dotNETCLRNetworkingEntry.name: dotNETCLRNetworkingEntry
dotNETCLRNetworkingEntry.description: Performance information for one particular instance of '.NET CLR Networking' object.

ncnBytesReceived.name: ncnBytesReceived
ncnBytesReceived.description: The cumulative total number of bytes received over all open socket connections since the process was started. This number includes data and any protocol information that is not defined by the TCP/IP protocol.

ncnBytesSent.name: ncnBytesSent
ncnBytesSent.description: The cumulative total number of bytes sent over all open socket connections since the process was started. This number includes data and any protocol information that is not defined by the TCP/IP protocol.

ncnConnectionsEstablished.name: ncnConnectionsEstablished
ncnConnectionsEstablished.description: The cumulative total number of socket connections established for this process since the process was started.

ncnDatagramsReceived.name: ncnDatagramsReceived
ncnDatagramsReceived.description: The cumulative total number of datagram packets received since the process was started.

ncnDatagramsSent.name: ncnDatagramsSent
ncnDatagramsSent.description: The cumulative total number of datagram packets sent since the process was started.

dotNETCLRRemotingTable.name: dotNETCLRRemotingTable
dotNETCLRRemotingTable.description: The Performance console .NET CLR Remoting category includes counters that provide information about the remoted objects that an application uses.

dotNETCLRRemotingEntry.name: dotNETCLRRemotingEntry
dotNETCLRRemotingEntry.description: Performance information for one particular instance of '.NET CLR Remoting' object.

ncrChannels.name: ncrChannels
ncrChannels.description: This counter displays the total number of remoting channels registered across all AppDomains since the start of the application. Channels are used to transport messages to and from remote objects.

ncrContextProxies.name: ncrContextProxies
ncrContextProxies.description: This counter displays the total number of remoting proxy objects created in this process since the start of the process. Proxy object acts as a representative of the remote objects and ensures that all calls made on the proxy are forwarded to the correct remote object instance.

ncrContextBoundClassesLoaded.name: ncrContextBoundClassesLoaded
ncrContextBoundClassesLoaded.description: This counter displays the current number of context-bound classes loaded. Classes that can be bound to a context are called context-bound classes; context-bound classes are marked with Context Attributes which provide usage rules for synchronization; thread affinity; transactions etc.

ncrContextBoundObjsAllocPerSec.name: ncrContextBoundObjsAllocPerSec
ncrContextBoundObjsAllocPerSec.description: This counter displays the number of context-bound objects allocated per second. Instances of classes that can be bound to a context are called context-bound objects; context-bound classes are marked with Context Attributes which provide usage rules for synchronization; thread affinity; transactions etc. This counter is not an average over time; it displays the difference between the values observed in the last two samples divided by the duration of the sample interval.

ncrContexts.name: ncrContexts
ncrContexts.description: This counter displays the current number of remoting contexts in the application. A context is a boundary containing a collection of objects with the same usage rules like synchronization; thread affinity; transactions etc.

ncrRemoteCallsPerSec.name: ncrRemoteCallsPerSec
ncrRemoteCallsPerSec.description: This counter displays the number of remote procedure calls invoked per second. A remote procedure call is a call on any object outside the caller;s AppDomain. This counter is not an average over time; it displays the difference between the values observed in the last two samples divided by the duration of the sample interval.

ncrTotalRemoteCalls.name: ncrTotalRemoteCalls
ncrTotalRemoteCalls.description: This counter displays the total number of remote procedure calls invoked since the start of this application. A remote procedure call is a call on any object outside the caller;s AppDomain.

dotNETCLRSecurityTable.name: dotNETCLRSecurityTable
dotNETCLRSecurityTable.description: The Performance console .NET CLR Security category includes counters that provide information about the security checks that the common language runtime performs for an application.

dotNETCLRSecurityEntry.name: dotNETCLRSecurityEntry
dotNETCLRSecurityEntry.description: Performance information for one particular instance of '.NET CLR Security' object.

ncsNumLinkTimeChecks.name: ncsNumLinkTimeChecks
ncsNumLinkTimeChecks.description: This counter displays the total number of linktime Code Access Security (CAS) checks since the start of the application. Linktime CAS checks are performed when a caller makes a call to a callee demanding a particular permission at JIT compile time; linktime check is performed once per caller. This count is not indicative of serious performance issues; its indicative of the security system activity.

ncsPercentTimeInRTChecks.name: ncsPercentTimeInRTChecks
ncsPercentTimeInRTChecks.description: This counter displays the percentage of elapsed time spent in performing runtime Code Access Security (CAS) checks since the last such check. CAS allows code to be trusted to varying degrees and enforces these varying levels of trust depending on code identity. This counter is updated at the end of a runtime security check; it represents the last observed value; its not an average.

ncsStackWalkDepth.name: ncsStackWalkDepth
ncsStackWalkDepth.description: This counter displays the depth of the stack during that last runtime Code Access Security check. Runtime Code Access Security check is performed by crawling the stack. This counter is not an average; it just displays the last observed value.

ncsTotalRuntimeChecks.name: ncsTotalRuntimeChecks
ncsTotalRuntimeChecks.description: This counter displays the total number of runtime Code Access Security (CAS) checks performed since the start of the application. Runtime CAS checks are performed when a caller makes a call to a callee demanding a particular permission; the runtime check is made on every call by the caller; the check is done by examining the current thread stack of the caller. This counter used together with 'Stack Walk Depth' is indicative of performance penalty for security checks.

fileReplicaConnTable.name: fileReplicaConnTable
fileReplicaConnTable.description: The FileReplicaConn performance object displays performance statistics of the REPLICACONN object that defines replica connections to distributed file system (Dfs) roots.

fileReplicaConnEntry.name: fileReplicaConnEntry
fileReplicaConnEntry.description: Performance information for one particular instance of 'FileReplicaConn' object.

frcAuthentications.name: frcAuthentications
frcAuthentications.description: The number of successful authentication checks made on packets received from the partner associated with this connection.

frcAuthenticationsInError.name: frcAuthenticationsInError
frcAuthenticationsInError.description: The cumulative number of authentication check failures detected on packets received from the partner associated with this connection.

frcBindings.name: frcBindings
frcBindings.description: The number of successful RPC bind requests to the FRS server on the partner associated with this connection.

frcBindingsInError.name: frcBindingsInError
frcBindingsInError.description: The cumulative number of unsuccessful RPC bind requests to the FRS server on the partner associated with this connection.

frcCommunicationTimeouts.name: frcCommunicationTimeouts
frcCommunicationTimeouts.description: The cumulative number of times a communication request has taken too long to the partner associated with this connection.

frcFetchBlocksReceived.name: frcFetchBlocksReceived
frcFetchBlocksReceived.description: The number of blocks of staging file data received from the partner associated with this connection. The underlying transport may break a block into a smaller number of packets on the wire.

frcFetchBlocksReceivedInBytes.name: frcFetchBlocksReceivedInBytes
frcFetchBlocksReceivedInBytes.description: The number of bytes of staging file data received from the partner associated with this connection.

frcFetchBlocksSent.name: frcFetchBlocksSent
frcFetchBlocksSent.description: The number of blocks of staging file data sent to the partner associated with this connection. The underlying transport may break a block into a smaller number of packets on the wire.

frcFetchBlocksSentInBytes.name: frcFetchBlocksSentInBytes
frcFetchBlocksSentInBytes.description: The number of bytes of staging file data sent to the partner associated with this connection.

frcFetchRequestsReceived.name: frcFetchRequestsReceived
frcFetchRequestsReceived.description: The number of staging files received from the partner associated with this connection.

frcFetchRequestsSent.name: frcFetchRequestsSent
frcFetchRequestsSent.description: The number of staging files requested from the partner associated with this connection.
