terminalServicesSessionTable.name: terminalServicesSessionTable
terminalServicesSessionTable.description: The Terminal Services Session object provides per-session resource statistics such as packet and frame transmission data, errors, and cache activity for Terminal Services.

terminalServicesSessionEntry.name: terminalServicesSessionEntry
terminalServicesSessionEntry.description: Performance information for one particular instance of 'Terminal Services Session' object.

tssPercentPrivilegedTime.name: tssPercentPrivilegedTime
tssPercentPrivilegedTime.description: % Privileged Time is the percentage of elapsed time that the process threads spent executing code in privileged mode. When a Windows system service is called, the service will often run in privileged mode to gain access to system-private data. Such data is protected from access by threads executing in user mode. Calls to the system can be explicit or implicit, such as page faults or interrupts. Unlike some early operating systems, Windows uses process boundaries for subsystem protection in addition to the traditional protection of user and privileged modes. Some work done by Windows on behalf of the application might appear in other subsystem processes in addition to the privileged time in the process.

tssPercentProcessorTime.name: tssPercentProcessorTime
tssPercentProcessorTime.description: % Processor Time is the percentage of elapsed time that all of process threads used the processor to execution instructions. An instruction is the basic unit of execution in a computer, a thread is the object that executes instructions, and a process is the object created when a program is run. Code executed to handle some hardware interrupts and trap conditions are included in this count.

tssPercentUserTime.name: tssPercentUserTime
tssPercentUserTime.description: % User Time is the percentage of elapsed time that the process threads spent executing code in user mode. Applications, environment subsystems, and integral subsystems execute in user mode. Code executing in user mode cannot damage the integrity of the Windows executive, kernel, and device drivers. Unlike some early operating systems, Windows uses process boundaries for subsystem protection in addition to the traditional protection of user and privileged modes. Some work done by Windows on behalf of the application might appear in other subsystem processes in addition to the privileged time in the process.

tssHandleCount.name: tssHandleCount
tssHandleCount.description: The total number of handles currently open by this process. This number is equal to the sum of the handles currently open by each thread in this process.

tssInputAsyncFrameError.name: tssInputAsyncFrameError
tssInputAsyncFrameError.description: Number of input async framing errors. These can be caused by a noisy transmission line. Using a smaller packet size may help in some cases.

tssInputAsyncOverflow.name: tssInputAsyncOverflow
tssInputAsyncOverflow.description: Number of input async overflow errors. These can be caused by a lack of buffer space available on the host.

tssInputAsyncOverrun.name: tssInputAsyncOverrun
tssInputAsyncOverrun.description: Number of input async overrun errors. These can be caused by the baud rate being faster than the computer can handle, or a non-16550 serial line is used. Overruns can also occur if too many high speed serial lines are active at one time for the processor's power.

tssInputAsyncParityError.name: tssInputAsyncParityError
tssInputAsyncParityError.description: Number of input async parity errors. These can be caused by a noisy transmission line

tssInputBytes.name: tssInputBytes
tssInputBytes.description: Number of bytes input on this session that includes all protocol overhead.

tssInputCompressFlushes.name: tssInputCompressFlushes
tssInputCompressFlushes.description: Number of input compression dictionary flushes. When the data can not be compressed, the compression dictionary is flushed so that newer data has a better chance of being compressed. Some causes of data not compressing includes transferring compressed files over Client Drive Mapping.

tssInputCompressedBytes.name: tssInputCompressedBytes
tssInputCompressedBytes.description: Number of bytes input after compression. This number compared with the Total Bytes input is the compression ratio.

tssInputCompressionRatio.name: tssInputCompressionRatio
tssInputCompressionRatio.description: Compression ratio of the server input data stream.

tssInputErrors.name: tssInputErrors
tssInputErrors.description: Number of input errors of all types. Some example input errors are lost ACK's, badly formed packets, etc.

tssInputFrames.name: tssInputFrames
tssInputFrames.description: Number of frames (packets) input on this Session.

tssInputTimeouts.name: tssInputTimeouts
tssInputTimeouts.description: The total number of timeouts on the communication line as seen from the client side of the connection. These are typically the result of a noisy line. On some high latency networks, this could be the result of the protocol timeout being too short. Increasing the protocol timeout on these types of lines will improve performance by reducing needless re-transmissions.

tssInputTransportErrors.name: tssInputTransportErrors
tssInputTransportErrors.description: Number of Terminal Services transport-level errors on input.

tssInputWaitForOutBuf.name: tssInputWaitForOutBuf
tssInputWaitForOutBuf.description: The number of times that a wait for an available send buffer was done by the protocols on the client side of the connection.

tssInputWdBytes.name: tssInputWdBytes
tssInputWdBytes.description: Number of bytes input on this session after all protocol overhead has been removed.

tssInputWdFrames.name: tssInputWdFrames
tssInputWdFrames.description: The number of frames input after any additional protocol added frames have been removed.

tssOutputAsyncFrameError.name: tssOutputAsyncFrameError
tssOutputAsyncFrameError.description: Number of output async framing errors. This could be caused by a hardware or line problem.

tssOutputAsyncOverflow.name: tssOutputAsyncOverflow
tssOutputAsyncOverflow.description: Number of output async overflow errors.

tssOutputAsyncOverrun.name: tssOutputAsyncOverrun
tssOutputAsyncOverrun.description: Number of output async overrun errors.

tssOutputAsyncParityError.name: tssOutputAsyncParityError
tssOutputAsyncParityError.description: Number of output async parity errors. These can be caused by a hardware or line problem.

tssOutputBytes.name: tssOutputBytes
tssOutputBytes.description: Number of bytes output on this Session that includes all protocol overhead.

tssOutputCompressFlushes.name: tssOutputCompressFlushes
tssOutputCompressFlushes.description: Number of output compression dictionary flushes. When the data can not be compressed, the compression dictionary is flushed so that newer data has a better chance of being compressed. Some causes of data not compressing includes transfering compressed files over Client Drive Mapping.

tssOutputCompressedBytes.name: tssOutputCompressedBytes
tssOutputCompressedBytes.description: Number of bytes output after compression. This number compared with the Total Bytes output is the compression ratio.

tssOutputCompressionRatio.name: tssOutputCompressionRatio
tssOutputCompressionRatio.description: Compression ratio of the server output data stream.

tssOutputErrors.name: tssOutputErrors
tssOutputErrors.description: Number of output errors of all types. Some example output errors are lost ACK's, badly formed packets, etc.

tssOutputFrames.name: tssOutputFrames
tssOutputFrames.description: Number of frames (packets) output on this session.

tssOutputTimeouts.name: tssOutputTimeouts
tssOutputTimeouts.description: The total number of timeouts on the communication line from the host side of the connection. These are typically the result of a noisy line. On some high latency networks, this could be the result of the protocol timeout being too short. Increasing the protocol timeout on these types of lines will improve performance by reducing needless re-transmissions.

tssOutputTransportErrors.name: tssOutputTransportErrors
tssOutputTransportErrors.description: Number of Terminal Services transport-level errors on output.

tssOutputWaitForOutBuf.name: tssOutputWaitForOutBuf
tssOutputWaitForOutBuf.description: This is the number of times that a wait for an available send buffer was done by the protocol on the server side of the connection.

tssOutputWdBytes.name: tssOutputWdBytes
tssOutputWdBytes.description: Number of bytes output on this session after all protocol overhead has been removed.

tssOutputWdFrames.name: tssOutputWdFrames
tssOutputWdFrames.description: The number of frames output before any additional protocol frames have been added.

tssPageFaultsPerSec.name: tssPageFaultsPerSec
tssPageFaultsPerSec.description: Page Faults/sec is the rate at which page faults by the threads executing in this process are occurring. A page fault occurs when a thread refers to a virtual memory page that is not in its working set in main memory. This may not cause the page to be fetched from disk if it is on the standby list and hence already in main memory, or if it is in use by another process with whom the page is shared.

tssPageFileBytes.name: tssPageFileBytes
tssPageFileBytes.description: Page File Bytes is the current amount of virtual memory, in bytes, that this process has reserved for use in the paging file(s). Paging files are used to store pages of memory used by the process that are not contained in other files. Paging files are shared by all processes, and the lack of space in paging files can prevent other processes from allocating memory. If there is no paging file, this counter reflects the current amount of virtual memory that the process has reserved for use in physical memory.

tssPageFileBytesPeak.name: tssPageFileBytesPeak
tssPageFileBytesPeak.description: Page File Bytes Peak is the maximum amount of virtual memory, in bytes, that this process has reserved for use in the paging file(s). Paging files are used to store pages of memory used by the process that are not contained in other files. Paging files are shared by all processes, and the lack of space in paging files can prevent other processes from allocating memory. If there is no paging file, this counter reflects the maximum amount of virtual memory that the process has reserved for use in physical memory.

tssPoolNonpagedBytes.name: tssPoolNonpagedBytes
tssPoolNonpagedBytes.description: Pool Nonpaged Bytes is the size, in bytes, of the nonpaged pool, an area of system memory (physical memory used by the operating system) for objects that cannot be written to disk, but must remain in physical memory as long as they are allocated. Memory\\Pool Nonpaged Bytes is calculated differently than Process\\Pool Nonpaged Bytes, so it might not equal Process\\Pool Nonpaged Bytes\\_Total. This counter displays the last observed value only; it is not an average.

tssPoolPagedBytes.name: tssPoolPagedBytes
tssPoolPagedBytes.description: Pool Paged Bytes is the size, in bytes, of the paged pool, an area of system memory (physical memory used by the operating system) for objects that can be written to disk when they are not being used. Memory\\Pool Paged Bytes is calculated differently than Process\\Pool Paged Bytes, so it might not equal Process\\Pool Paged Bytes\\_Total. This counter displays the last observed value only; it is not an average.

tssPrivateBytes.name: tssPrivateBytes
tssPrivateBytes.description: Private Bytes is the current size, in bytes, of memory that this process has allocated that cannot be shared with other processes.

tssProtocolBitmapCacheHitRatio.name: tssProtocolBitmapCacheHitRatio
tssProtocolBitmapCacheHitRatio.description: Hit ratio in the protocol bitmap cache. A higher hit ratio means better performance since data transmissions are reduced. Low hit ratios are due to the screen updating with new information that is either not re-used, or is flushed out of the client cache.

tssProtocolBitmapCacheHits.name: tssProtocolBitmapCacheHits
tssProtocolBitmapCacheHits.description: Number of hits in the protocol bitmap cache.

tssProtocolBitmapCacheReads.name: tssProtocolBitmapCacheReads
tssProtocolBitmapCacheReads.description: Number of references to the protocol bitmap cache.

tssProtocolBrushCacheHitRatio.name: tssProtocolBrushCacheHitRatio
tssProtocolBrushCacheHitRatio.description: Hit ratio in the protocol brush cache. A higher hit ratio means better performance since data transmissions are reduced. Low hit ratios are due to the screen updating with new information that is either not re-used, or is flushed out of the client cache.

tssProtocolBrushCacheHits.name: tssProtocolBrushCacheHits
tssProtocolBrushCacheHits.description: Number of hits in the protocol brush cache.

tssProtocolBrushCacheReads.name: tssProtocolBrushCacheReads
tssProtocolBrushCacheReads.description: Number of references to the protocol brush cache.

tssProtocolGlyphCacheHitRatio.name: tssProtocolGlyphCacheHitRatio
tssProtocolGlyphCacheHitRatio.description: Hit ratio in the protocol glyph cache. A higher hit ratio means better performance since data transmissions are reduced. Low hit ratios are due to the screen updating with new information that is either not re-used, or is flushed out of the client cache.

tssProtocolGlyphCacheHits.name: tssProtocolGlyphCacheHits
tssProtocolGlyphCacheHits.description: Number of hits in the protocol glyph cache.

tssProtocolGlyphCacheReads.name: tssProtocolGlyphCacheReads
tssProtocolGlyphCacheReads.description: Number of references to the protocol glyph cache.

tssProtocolSvScrnBtmpCachHtRatio.name: tssProtocolSvScrnBtmpCachHtRatio
tssProtocolSvScrnBtmpCachHtRatio.description: Hit ratio in the protocol save screen bitmap cache. A higher hit ratio means better performance since data transmissions are reduced. Low hit ratios are due to the screen updating with new information that is either not re-used, or is flushed out of the client cache.

tssProtocolSvScrnBtmpCachHts.name: tssProtocolSvScrnBtmpCachHts
tssProtocolSvScrnBtmpCachHts.description: Number of hits in the protocol save screen bitmap cache.

tssProtocolSvScrnBtmpCachReads.name: tssProtocolSvScrnBtmpCachReads
tssProtocolSvScrnBtmpCachReads.description: Number of references to the protocol save screen bitmap cache.

tssThreadCount.name: tssThreadCount
tssThreadCount.description: The number of threads currently active in this process. An instruction is the basic unit of execution in a processor, and a thread is the object that executes instructions. Every running process has at least one thread.

tssTotalAsyncFrameError.name: tssTotalAsyncFrameError
tssTotalAsyncFrameError.description: Total number of async framing errors. These can be caused by a noisy transmission line. Using a smaller packet size may help in some cases.

tssTotalAsyncOverflow.name: tssTotalAsyncOverflow
tssTotalAsyncOverflow.description: Total number of async overflow errors. These can be caused by a lack of buffer space available on the host.

tssTotalAsyncOverrun.name: tssTotalAsyncOverrun
tssTotalAsyncOverrun.description: Total number of async overrun errors. These can be caused by the baud rate being faster than the computer can handle, or a non-16550 serial line is used. Overruns can also occur if too many high speed serial lines are active at one time for the processor's power.

tssTotalAsyncParityError.name: tssTotalAsyncParityError
tssTotalAsyncParityError.description: Total number of async parity errors. These can be caused by a noisy transmission line.

tssTotalBytes.name: tssTotalBytes
tssTotalBytes.description: Total number of bytes on this Session that includes all protocol overhead.

tssTotalCompressFlushes.name: tssTotalCompressFlushes
tssTotalCompressFlushes.description: Total number of compression dictionary flushes. When the data can not be compressed, the compression dictionary is flushed so that newer data has a better chance of being compressed. Some causes of data not compressing includes transfering compressed files over Client Drive Mapping.

tssTotalCompressedBytes.name: tssTotalCompressedBytes
tssTotalCompressedBytes.description: Total number of bytes after compression. This number compared with the total bytes is the compression ratio.

tssTotalCompressionRatio.name: tssTotalCompressionRatio
tssTotalCompressionRatio.description: Total compression ratio of the server data stream.

tssTotalErrors.name: tssTotalErrors
tssTotalErrors.description: Total number of errors of all types. Some example errors are lost ACK's, badly formed packets, etc.

tssTotalFrames.name: tssTotalFrames
tssTotalFrames.description: Total number of frames (packets) on this Session.

tssTotalProtocolCacheHitRatio.name: tssTotalProtocolCacheHitRatio
tssTotalProtocolCacheHitRatio.description: Overall hit ratio for all protocol caches.

tssTotalProtocolCacheHits.name: tssTotalProtocolCacheHits
tssTotalProtocolCacheHits.description: Total hits in all protocol caches. The protocol caches Windows objects that are likely to be re-used to avoid having to re-send them on the transmission line. Example objects are Windows icons and brushes. Hits in the cache represent objects that did not need to be re-sent.

tssTotalProtocolCacheReads.name: tssTotalProtocolCacheReads
tssTotalProtocolCacheReads.description: Total references to all protocol caches.

tssTotalTimeouts.name: tssTotalTimeouts
tssTotalTimeouts.description: The total number of timeouts on the communication line from both the host and client sides of the connection. These are typically the result of a noisy line. On some high latency networks, this could be the result of the protocol timeout being too short. Increasing the protocol timeout on these types of lines will improve performance by reducing needless re-transmissions.

tssTotalTransportErrors.name: tssTotalTransportErrors
tssTotalTransportErrors.description: Total number of Terminal Services transport-level errors.

tssTotalWaitForOutBuf.name: tssTotalWaitForOutBuf
tssTotalWaitForOutBuf.description: The number of times that a wait for an available send buffer was done by the protocols on both the server and client sides of the connection.

tssTotalWdBytes.name: tssTotalWdBytes
tssTotalWdBytes.description: Total number of bytes on this Session after all protocol overhead has been removed.

tssTotalWdFrames.name: tssTotalWdFrames
tssTotalWdFrames.description: The total number of frames input and output before any additional protocol frames have been added.

tssVirtualBytes.name: tssVirtualBytes
tssVirtualBytes.description: Virtual Bytes is the current size, in bytes, of the virtual address space the process is using. Use of virtual address space does not necessarily imply corresponding use of either disk or main memory pages. Virtual space is finite, and the process can limit its ability to load libraries.

tssVirtualBytesPeak.name: tssVirtualBytesPeak
tssVirtualBytesPeak.description: Virtual Bytes Peak is the maximum size, in bytes, of virtual address space the process has used at any one time. Use of virtual address space does not necessarily imply corresponding use of either disk or main memory pages. However, virtual space is finite, and the process might limit its ability to load libraries.

tssWorkingSet.name: tssWorkingSet
tssWorkingSet.description: Working Set is the current size, in bytes, of the Working Set of this process. The Working Set is the set of memory pages touched recently by the threads in the process. If free memory in the computer is above a threshold, pages are left in the Working Set of a process even if they are not in use. When free memory falls below a threshold, pages are trimmed from Working Sets. If they are needed they will then be soft-faulted back into the Working Set before leaving main memory.

tssWorkingSetPeak.name: tssWorkingSetPeak
tssWorkingSetPeak.description: Working Set Peak is the maximum size, in bytes, of the Working Set of this process at any point in time. The Working Set is the set of memory pages touched recently by the threads in the process. If free memory in the computer is above a threshold, pages are left in the Working Set of a process even if they are not in use. When free memory falls below a threshold, pages are trimmed from Working Sets. If they are needed they will then be soft-faulted back into the Working Set before they leave main memory.

threadTable.name: threadTable
threadTable.description: The Thread performance object consists of counters that measure aspects of thread behavior. A thread is the basic object that executes instructions on a processor. All running processes have at least one thread.

threadEntry.name: threadEntry
threadEntry.description: Performance information for one particular instance of 'Thread' object.

threadPercentPrivilegedTime.name: threadPercentPrivilegedTime
threadPercentPrivilegedTime.description: % Privileged Time is the percentage of elapsed time that the process threads spent executing code in privileged mode. When a Windows system service in called, the service will often run in privileged mode to gain access to system-private data. Such data is protected from access by threads executing in user mode. Calls to the system can be explicit or implicit, such as page faults or interrupts. Unlike some early operating systems, Windows uses process boundaries for subsystem protection in addition to the traditional protection of user and privileged modes. Some work done by Windows on behalf of the application might appear in other subsystem processes in addition to the privileged time in the process.

threadPercentProcessorTime.name: threadPercentProcessorTime
threadPercentProcessorTime.description: % Processor Time is the percentage of elapsed time that all of process threads used the processor to execution instructions. An instruction is the basic unit of execution in a computer, a thread is the object that executes instructions, and a process is the object created when a program is run. Code executed to handle some hardware interrupts and trap conditions are included in this count.

threadPercentUserTime.name: threadPercentUserTime
threadPercentUserTime.description: % User Time is the percentage of elapsed time that this thread has spent executing code in user mode. Applications, environment subsystems, and integral subsystems execute in user mode. Code executing in user mode cannot damage the integrity of the Windows NT Executive, Kernel, and device drivers. Unlike some early operating systems, Windows NT uses process boundaries for subsystem protection in addition to the traditional protection of user and privileged modes. These subsystem processes provide additional protection. Therefore, some work done by Windows NT on behalf of your application might appear in other subsystem processes in addition to the privileged time in your process.

threadContextSwitchesPerSec.name: threadContextSwitchesPerSec
threadContextSwitchesPerSec.description: Context Switches/sec is the rate of switches from one thread to another. Thread switches can occur either inside of a single process or across processes. A thread switch can be caused either by one thread asking another for information, or by a thread being preempted by another, higher priority thread becoming ready to run. Unlike some early operating systems, Windows NT uses process boundaries for subsystem protection in addition to the traditional protection of user and privileged modes. These subsystem processes provide additional protection. Therefore, some work done by Windows NT on behalf of an application appear in other subsystem processes in addition to the privileged time in the application. Switching to the subsystem process causes one Context Switch in the application thread. Switching back causes another Context Switch in the subsystem thread.

threadElapsedTime.name: threadElapsedTime
threadElapsedTime.description: The total elapsed time (in seconds) this thread has been running.

threadIDProcess.name: threadIDProcess
threadIDProcess.description: ID Process is the unique identifier of this process. ID Process numbers are reused, so they only identify a process for the lifetime of that process.

threadIDThread.name: threadIDThread
threadIDThread.description: ID Thread is the unique identifier of this thread. ID Thread numbers are reused, so they only identify a thread for the lifetime of that thread.

threadPriorityBase.name: threadPriorityBase
threadPriorityBase.description: The current base priority of this thread. The system can raise the thread's dynamic priority above the base priority if the thread is handling user input, or lower it towards the base priority if the thread becomes compute bound.

threadPriorityCurrent.name: threadPriorityCurrent
threadPriorityCurrent.description: The current dynamic priority of this thread. The system can raise the thread's dynamic priority above the base priority if the thread is handling user input, or lower it towards the base priority if the thread becomes compute bound.

threadStartAddress.name: threadStartAddress
threadStartAddress.description: Starting virtual address for this thread.

threadThreadState.name: threadThreadState
threadThreadState.description: Thread State is the current state of the thread. It is 0 for Initialized, 1 for Ready, 2 for Running, 3 for Standby, 4 for Terminated, 5 for Wait, 6 for Transition, 7 for Unknown. A Running thread is using a processor; a Standby thread is about to use one. A Ready thread wants to use a processor, but is waiting for a processor because none are free. A thread in Transition is waiting for a resource in order to execute, such as waiting for its execution stack to be paged in from disk. A Waiting thread has no use for the processor because it is waiting for a peripheral operation to complete or a resource to become free.

threadThreadWaitReason.name: threadThreadWaitReason
threadThreadWaitReason.description: Thread Wait Reason is only applicable when the thread is in the Wait state (see Thread State). It is 0 or 7 when the thread is waiting for the Executive, 1 or 8 for a Free Page, 2 or 9 for a Page In, 3 or 10 for a Pool Allocation, 4 or 11 for an Execution Delay, 5 or 12 for a Suspended condition, 6 or 13 for a User Request, 14 for an Event Pair High, 15 for an Event Pair Low, 16 for an LPC Receive, 17 for an LPC Reply, 18 for Virtual Memory, 19 for a Page Out; 20 and higher are not assigned at the time of this writing. Event Pairs are used to communicate with protected subsystems (see Context Switches).

udpV4.name: udpV4
udpV4.description: The UDP performance object consists of counters that measure the rates at which User Data Protocol (UDP) datagrams are sent and received using the UDP. It includes counters that monitor UDP errors.

udpV4DatagramsNoPortPerSec.name: udpV4DatagramsNoPortPerSec
udpV4DatagramsNoPortPerSec.description: Datagrams No Port/sec is the rate of received UDP datagrams for which there was no application at the destination port.

udpV4DatagramsReceivedErrors.name: udpV4DatagramsReceivedErrors
udpV4DatagramsReceivedErrors.description: Datagrams Received Errors is the number of received UDP datagrams that could not be delivered for reasons other than the lack of an application at the destination port.

udpV4DatagramsReceivedPerSec.name: udpV4DatagramsReceivedPerSec
udpV4DatagramsReceivedPerSec.description: Datagrams Received/sec is the rate at which UDP datagrams are delivered to UDP users.

udpV4DatagramsSentPerSec.name: udpV4DatagramsSentPerSec
udpV4DatagramsSentPerSec.description: Datagrams Sent/sec is the rate at which UDP datagrams are sent from the entity.

udpV4DatagramsPerSec.name: udpV4DatagramsPerSec
udpV4DatagramsPerSec.description: Datagrams/sec is the rate at which UDP datagrams are sent or received by the entity.

udpV6DatagramsNoPortPerSec.name: udpV6DatagramsNoPortPerSec
udpV6DatagramsNoPortPerSec.description: Datagrams No Port/sec is the rate of received UDP datagrams for which there was no application at the destination port.

udpV6DatagramsReceivedErrors.name: udpV6DatagramsReceivedErrors
udpV6DatagramsReceivedErrors.description: Datagrams Received Errors is the number of received UDP datagrams that could not be delivered for reasons other than the lack of an application at the destination port.

udpV6DatagramsReceivedPerSec.name: udpV6DatagramsReceivedPerSec
udpV6DatagramsReceivedPerSec.description: Datagrams Received/sec is the rate at which UDP datagrams are delivered to UDP users.

udpV6DatagramsSentPerSec.name: udpV6DatagramsSentPerSec
udpV6DatagramsSentPerSec.description: Datagrams Sent/sec is the rate at which UDP datagrams are sent from the entity.

udpV6DatagramsPerSec.name: udpV6DatagramsPerSec
udpV6DatagramsPerSec.description: Datagrams/sec is the rate at which UDP datagrams are sent or received by the entity.

webServiceTable.name: webServiceTable
webServiceTable.description: The Web Service object counters installed with Internet Information Service monitor file transfer rates, bandwidth usage, and connection rates. You can view performance data for all instances of this object (using the _Total instance) or for specific instances, such as the Default Web Site or Administration Web Site instances. In addition to these counters, counters supplied by the Internet Information Services Global performance object combine data for the Web service with the performance data they report for IIS as a whole. For more information, see the Internet Information Services Global object.

webServiceEntry.name: webServiceEntry
webServiceEntry.description: Performance information for one particular instance of 'Web Service' object.

wsAnonymousUsersPerSec.name: wsAnonymousUsersPerSec
wsAnonymousUsersPerSec.description: The rate users are making anonymous connections to the Web service.

wsBytesReceivedPerSec.name: wsBytesReceivedPerSec
wsBytesReceivedPerSec.description: Bytes Received/sec is the rate that data bytes are received by the Web service.

wsBytesSentPerSec.name: wsBytesSentPerSec
wsBytesSentPerSec.description: Bytes Sent/sec is the rate data bytes are being sent by the Web service.

wsBytesTotalPerSec.name: wsBytesTotalPerSec
wsBytesTotalPerSec.description: Bytes Total/sec is the sum of Bytes Sent/sec and Bytes Received/sec. This is the total rate of bytes transferred by the Web service.

wsCGIRqstsPerSec.name: wsCGIRqstsPerSec
wsCGIRqstsPerSec.description: The rate CGI requests are received by the Web service.

wsConnAtmpsPerSec.name: wsConnAtmpsPerSec
wsConnAtmpsPerSec.description: The rate that connections to the Web service are being attempted.

wsCopyRqstsPerSec.name: wsCopyRqstsPerSec
wsCopyRqstsPerSec.description: The rate HTTP requests using the COPY method are made. Copy requests are used for copying files and directories.

wsCurrentAnonymousUsers.name: wsCurrentAnonymousUsers
wsCurrentAnonymousUsers.description: Current Anonymous Users is the number of users who currently have an anonymous connection using the Web service.

wsCurrentBlkdAsyncIORqsts.name: wsCurrentBlkdAsyncIORqsts
wsCurrentBlkdAsyncIORqsts.description: Current requests temporarily blocked due to bandwidth throttling settings.

wsCurrentCALCountForSSLConns.name: wsCurrentCALCountForSSLConns
wsCurrentCALCountForSSLConns.description: This counter is no longer valid. Value will always be zero.

wsCurrentCALCountForAuthdUsers.name: wsCurrentCALCountForAuthdUsers
wsCurrentCALCountForAuthdUsers.description: This counter is no longer valid. Value will always be zero.

wsCurrentCGIRqsts.name: wsCurrentCGIRqsts
wsCurrentCGIRqsts.description: Current CGI Requests is the current number of CGI requests being simultaneously processed by the Web service.

wsCurrentConns.name: wsCurrentConns
wsCurrentConns.description: Current Connections is the current number of connections established with the Web service.

wsCurrentISAPIExtensionRqsts.name: wsCurrentISAPIExtensionRqsts
wsCurrentISAPIExtensionRqsts.description: Current ISAPI Extension Requests is the current number of ISAPI requests being simultaneously processed by the Web service.

wsCurrentNonAnonymousUsers.name: wsCurrentNonAnonymousUsers
wsCurrentNonAnonymousUsers.description: Current NonAnonymous Users is the number of users who currently have a non-anonymous connection using the Web service.

wsCurrentBlkdBandwidthBytes.name: wsCurrentBlkdBandwidthBytes
wsCurrentBlkdBandwidthBytes.description: Current bytes temporarily blocked due to bandwidth throttling settings.

wsDeleteRqstsPerSec.name: wsDeleteRqstsPerSec
wsDeleteRqstsPerSec.description: The rate HTTP requests using the DELETE method are made. Delete requests are generally used for file removals.

wsFilesReceivedPerSec.name: wsFilesReceivedPerSec
wsFilesReceivedPerSec.description: The rate files are received by the Web service.

wsFilesSentPerSec.name: wsFilesSentPerSec
wsFilesSentPerSec.description: The rate files are sent by the Web service.

wsFilesPerSec.name: wsFilesPerSec
wsFilesPerSec.description: The rate files are transferred, that is, sent and received by the Web service.

wsGetRqstsPerSec.name: wsGetRqstsPerSec
wsGetRqstsPerSec.description: The rate HTTP requests using the GET method are made. Get requests are the most common HTTP request.

wsHeadRqstsPerSec.name: wsHeadRqstsPerSec
wsHeadRqstsPerSec.description: The rate HTTP requests using the HEAD method are made. Head requests generally indicate a client is querying the state of a document they already have to see if it needs to be refreshed.

wsISAPIExtensionRqstsPerSec.name: wsISAPIExtensionRqstsPerSec
wsISAPIExtensionRqstsPerSec.description: The rate that ISAPI Extension requests are received by the Web service.

wsLockRqstsPerSec.name: wsLockRqstsPerSec
wsLockRqstsPerSec.description: The rate HTTP requests using the LOCK method are made. Lock requests are used to lock a file for one user so that only that user can modify the file.

wsLockedErrorsPerSec.name: wsLockedErrorsPerSec
wsLockedErrorsPerSec.description: The rate of errors due to requests that couldn't be satisfied by the server because the requested document was locked. These are generally reported as an HTTP 423 error code to the client.

wsLogonAtmpsPerSec.name: wsLogonAtmpsPerSec
wsLogonAtmpsPerSec.description: The rate that logons to the Web service are being attempted.

wsMaximumAnonymousUsers.name: wsMaximumAnonymousUsers
wsMaximumAnonymousUsers.description: Maximum Anonymous Users is the maximum number of users who established concurrent anonymous connections using the Web service (since service startup).

wsMaximumCALCountForSSLConns.name: wsMaximumCALCountForSSLConns
wsMaximumCALCountForSSLConns.description: This counter is no longer valid. Value will always be zero.

wsMaximumCALCountForAuthdUsers.name: wsMaximumCALCountForAuthdUsers
wsMaximumCALCountForAuthdUsers.description: This counter is no longer valid. Value will always be zero.

wsProppatchRqstsPerSec.description: The rate HTTP requests using the PROPPATCH method are made. Proppatch requests set property values on files and directories.

wsPutRqstsPerSec.name: wsPutRqstsPerSec
wsPutRqstsPerSec.description: The rate HTTP requests using the PUT method are made.

wsSearchRqstsPerSec.name: wsSearchRqstsPerSec
wsSearchRqstsPerSec.description: The rate HTTP requests using the SEARCH method are made. Search requests are used to query the server to find resources that match a set of conditions provided by the client.

wsTotalDeleteRqsts.name: wsTotalDeleteRqsts
wsTotalDeleteRqsts.description: Total Delete Requests is the number of HTTP requests using the DELETE method (since service startup). Delete requests are generally used for file removals.

wsTotalLockedErrors.description: Total Locked Errors is the number of requests that couldn't be satisfied by the server because the requested was locked (since service startup). These are generally reported as an HTTP 423 error code to the client.

wsTotalLogonAtmps.name: wsTotalLogonAtmps

wsTotalMkcolRqsts.description: Total Mkcol Requests is the number of HTTP requests using the MKCOL method (since service startup). Mkcol requests are used to create directories on the server.

wsTotalMoveRqsts.name: wsTotalMoveRqsts
wsTotalMoveRqsts.description: Total Move Requests is the number of HTTP requests using the MOVE method (since service startup). Move requests are used for moving files and directories.

wsTotalNonAnonymousUsers.name: wsTotalNonAnonymousUsers
wsTotalNonAnonymousUsers.description: Total NonAnonymous Users is the total number of users who established a non-anonymous connection with the Web service (since service startup).

wsTotalNotFoundErrors.name: wsTotalNotFoundErrors
wsTotalNotFoundErrors.description: Total Not Found Errors is the number of requests that couldn't be satisfied by the server because the requested document could not be found (since service startup). These are generally reported as an HTTP 404 error code to the client.

wsTotalOptionsRqsts.name: wsTotalOptionsRqsts
wsTotalOptionsRqsts.description: Total Options Requests is the number of HTTP requests using the OPTIONS method (since service startup).

wsTotalOtherRqstMethods.name: wsTotalOtherRqstMethods
wsTotalOtherRqstMethods.description: Total Other Request Methods is the number of HTTP requests that are not OPTIONS, GET, HEAD, POST, PUT, DELETE, TRACE, MOVE, COPY, MKCOL, PROPFIND, PROPPATCH, SEARCH, LOCK or UNLOCK methods (since service startup).

wsTotalPostRqsts.name: wsTotalPostRqsts
wsTotalPostRqsts.description: Total Post Requests is the number of HTTP requests using the POST method (since service startup).

wsTotalPropfindRqsts.name: wsTotalPropfindRqsts
wsTotalPropfindRqsts.description: Total Propfind Requests is the number of HTTP requests using the PROPFIND method (since service startup). Propfind requests retrieve property values on files and directories.

wsTotalProppatchRqsts.name: wsTotalProppatchRqsts
wsTotalProppatchRqsts.description: Total Proppatch Requests is the number of HTTP requests using the PROPPATCH method (since service startup). Proppatch requests set property values on files and directories.

wsTotalPutRqsts.name: wsTotalPutRqsts
wsTotalPutRqsts.description: Total Put Requests is the number of HTTP requests using the PUT method (since service startup).

wsTotalRejectedAsyncIORqsts.name: wsTotalRejectedAsyncIORqsts
wsTotalRejectedAsyncIORqsts.description: Total requests rejected due to bandwidth throttling settings (since service startup).

wsTotalSearchRqsts.name: wsTotalSearchRqsts
wsTotalSearchRqsts.description: Total Search Requests is the number of HTTP requests using the SEARCH method (since service startup). Search requests are used to query the server to find resources that match a set of conditions provided by the client.

wsTotalTraceRqsts.description: Total Trace Requests is the number of HTTP requests using the TRACE method (since service startup). Trace requests allow the client to see what is being received at the end of the request chain and use the information for diagnostic purposes.

wsTotalUnlockRqsts.description: Total Unlock Requests is the number of HTTP requests using the UNLOCK method (since service startup). Unlock requests are used to remove locks from files.

wsUnlockRqstsPerSec.name: wsUnlockRqstsPerSec
wsUnlockRqstsPerSec.description: The rate HTTP requests using the UNLOCK method are made. Unlock requests are used to remove locks from files.

This includes terminations that occurred because player inactivity and timeout limits were exceeded, as well as terminations that were due to events such as late reads.

wmppCurStreamingRTSPPlayers.name: wmppCurStreamingRTSPPlayers
wmppCurStreamingRTSPPlayers.description: Current Streaming RTSP Players is the current number of players being streamed data using the RTSP protocol. This does not include players that are stopped or paused.

wmppPeakConnectedPlayers.name: wmppPeakConnectedPlayers
wmppPeakConnectedPlayers.description: Peak Connected Players is the peak number of players that have connected since the last time the counter was reset.

wmppPeakOutDistAllocBandwdthKbps.name: wmppPeakOutDistAllocBandwdthKbps
wmppPeakOutDistAllocBandwdthKbps.description: Peak Outgoing Distribution Allocated Bandwidth is the peak bandwidth, in Kbps, allocated for all streams to distribution servers that have connected since the last time the server was reset.

wmppPeakOutDistConnections.name: wmppPeakOutDistConnections
wmppPeakOutDistConnections.description: Peak Outgoing Distribution Connections is the peak number of distribution servers that have connected since the last time the counter was reset.

wmppPeakPlayerAllocBandwidthKbps.name: wmppPeakPlayerAllocBandwidthKbps
wmppPeakPlayerAllocBandwidthKbps.description: Peak Player Allocated Bandwidth is the peak bandwidth, in Kbps, that was allocated for streams to players since the last time the counter was reset.

wmppPeakStreamingPlayers.name: wmppPeakStreamingPlayers
wmppPeakStreamingPlayers.description: Peak Streaming Players is the peak number of players that have been streamed data since the last time the counter was reset.

wmppTotalAdvertisements.name: wmppTotalAdvertisements
wmppTotalAdvertisements.description: Total Advertisements is the total number of advertisements that have been streamed from playlists since the last time the counter was reset.

wmppTotalConnectedPlayers.name: wmppTotalConnectedPlayers
wmppTotalConnectedPlayers.description: Total Connected Players is the total number of players that have connected since the last time the counter was reset.

wmppTotalFileBytesRead.name: wmppTotalFileBytesRead
wmppTotalFileBytesRead.description: Total File Bytes Read is the total number of file bytes read.

wmppTotalLateReads.name: wmppTotalLateReads
wmppTotalLateReads.description: Total Late Reads is the total number of late read operations since the last time the counter was reset.

wmppTotalOutDistBytesSent.name: wmppTotalOutDistBytesSent
wmppTotalOutDistBytesSent.description: Total Outgoing Distribution Bytes Sent is the total number of bytes streamed to all distribution servers since the last time the counter was reset.

wmppTotalOutDistConnections.name: wmppTotalOutDistConnections
wmppTotalOutDistConnections.description: Total Outgoing Distribution Connections is the total number of distribution servers that have connected since the last time the counter was reset.

wmppTotalPlayerBytesSent.name: wmppTotalPlayerBytesSent
wmppTotalPlayerBytesSent.description: Total Player Bytes Sent is the total number of bytes streamed to all players since the last time the counter was reset.

wmppTotalStreamDenials.name: wmppTotalStreamDenials
wmppTotalStreamDenials.description: Total Stream Denials is the total number of stream denials since the last time the counter was reset. This includes both denials that occurred due to failure to be authorized or authenticated, as well as denials that occurred because limits were exceeded.

wmppTotalStreamErrors.name: wmppTotalStreamErrors
wmppTotalStreamErrors.description: Total Stream Errors is the total number of stream errors due to dropped packets since the last time the counter was reset.

wmppTotalStreamTerminations.name: wmppTotalStreamTerminations
wmppTotalStreamTerminations.description: Total Stream Terminations is the total number of streams that were terminated due to inactivity or errors since the last time the counter was reset. This includes terminations that occurred because player inactivity and timeout limits were exceeded, as well as terminations that were due to events such as late reads.

wmppTotalStreamingPlayers.name: wmppTotalStreamingPlayers
wmppTotalStreamingPlayers.description: Total Streaming Players is the total number of players that have been streamed data since the last time the counter was reset.

windowsMediaStationService.name: windowsMediaStationService
windowsMediaStationService.description: The Windows Media Station Service performance object provides statistics about the Windows Media Station service that provides multicasting, distribution and storage functions for ASF streams.

wmssControllers.name: wmssControllers
wmssControllers.description: The number of controllers currently connected to the server.

wmssStations.name: wmssStations
wmssStations.description: The number of station objects that currently exist in the server.

wmssStreams.name: wmssStreams
wmssStreams.description: The number of stream objects that currently exist in the server.

windowsMediaUnicastService.name: windowsMediaUnicastService
windowsMediaUnicastService.description: The Windows Media Unicast Service performance object provides statistics about the Windows Media service Unicast service that provides unicasting functions for Advanced Streaming Format (ASF) streams.

wmusActiveLiveUnicastStreams.name: wmusActiveLiveUnicastStreams
wmusActiveLiveUnicastStreams.description: The number of Live Unicast streams that are being streamed.

wmusActiveStreams.name: wmusActiveStreams
wmusActiveStreams.description: The number of streams that are being streamed.

wmusActiveTCPStreams.name: wmusActiveTCPStreams
wmusActiveTCPStreams.description: The number of TCP streams that are being streamed.

wmusActiveUDPStreams.name: wmusActiveUDPStreams
wmusActiveUDPStreams.description: The number of UDP streams that are being streamed.

wmusAggregateReadRate.name: wmusAggregateReadRate
wmusAggregateReadRate.description: The total, aggregate rate (bytes/sec) of file reads.

wmusAggregateSendRate.name: wmusAggregateSendRate
wmusAggregateSendRate.description: The total, aggregate rate (bytes/sec) of stream transmission.

wmusAllocatedBandwidth.name: wmusAllocatedBandwidth
wmusAllocatedBandwidth.description: The bandwidth (bytes/sec) currently allocated by clients.

wmusAuthenticationRequests.name: wmusAuthenticationRequests
wmusAuthenticationRequests.description: The number of times an authentication plugin is called to authenticate a client. Depending on the protocol in use, either HTTP or Microsoft Media Server (MMS), a single client may be authenticated once or several times when accessing each piece of unicast co

wmusAuthenticationsDenied.name: wmusAuthenticationsDenied
wmusAuthenticationsDenied.description: The number of times clients are denied access to unicast content by authentication plugins. Clients are denied access by an authentication plugin when their IDs cannot be verified, no user accounts exist, or the authentication plugin is not working.

wmusAuthorizationRequests.name: wmusAuthorizationRequests
wmusAuthorizationRequests.description: The number of times an authorization plugin is called to authorize a client. Each client action, such as opening or playing unicast content, is separately authorized; therefore, the total number of authorization requests is greater than the number of connecte

wmusAuthorizationsRefused.name: wmusAuthorizationsRefused
wmusAuthorizationsRefused.description: The number of times clients are denied access to unicast content by authorization plugins. Plugins will deny access to clients based on their function; for example, a billing plugin may deny client access to unicast content if the user account contains insuff

wmusConnectedClients.name: wmusConnectedClients
wmusConnectedClients.description: The number of clients connected to this server.

wmusConnectionRate.name: wmusConnectionRate
wmusConnectionRate.description: The rate at which clients are connecting to the server.

wmusHTTPStreams.name: wmusHTTPStreams
wmusHTTPStreams.description: The number of HTTP streams being streamed.

wmusHTTPStreamsReadingHeader.name: wmusHTTPStreamsReadingHeader
wmusHTTPStreamsReadingHeader.description: The number of clients connected to the server via HTTP and reading a file header, but not yet streaming the unicast content. HTTP Streams Reading Header and HTTP Streams Reading Body equal the total number of clients connected to the server via HTTP, as indic

wmusHTTPStreamsStreamingBody.name: wmusHTTPStreamsStreamingBody
wmusHTTPStreamsStreamingBody.description: The number of connected clients that have read the file header and are actively streaming unicast content via HTTP. HTTP Streams Reading Body and HTTP Streams Reading Header equal the total number of clients connected to the server via HTTP, as indicated by H

wmusLateReads.name: wmusLateReads
wmusLateReads.description: The number of late read completions per second.

wmusPendingConnections.name: wmusPendingConnections
wmusPendingConnections.description: The number of clients attempting to connect to the server but are not yet connected. This number may be high if the server is running near maximum capacity and cannot process a large number of connection requests in a timely manner.

wmusPluginErrors.name: wmusPluginErrors
wmusPluginErrors.description: The number of times plugins failed to perform their function. For example, a plugin couldn't reach its user database, the plugin crashed, and so on.

wmusPluginEvents.name: wmusPluginEvents
wmusPluginEvents.description: The number of events reported to plugins. An indicator of how much the server is using external plugins.

wmusSchedulingRate.name: wmusSchedulingRate
wmusSchedulingRate.description: The rate (tasks/sec) at which tasks are being scheduled.

wmusStreamErrors.name: wmusStreamErrors
wmusStreamErrors.description: The cumulative number of errors occuring per second.

wmusStreamTerminations.name: wmusStreamTerminations
wmusStreamTerminations.description: The rate at which streams are being terminated due to errors.

wmusUDPResendRequests.name: wmusUDPResendRequests
wmusUDPResendRequests.description: The number of times clients ask the server to resend a data packet that was received in error. This value may be high when the server cannot send packets via UDP reliably. A good indicator of server or network overload.

wmusUDPResendsSent.name: wmusUDPResendsSent
wmusUDPResendsSent.description: The number of UDP Resend Requests processed by the server. Not all UDP Resend Requests are processed if the server is under a heavy load.

winsSrvrGroupConflictsPerSec.name: winsSrvrGroupConflictsPerSec
winsSrvrGroupConflictsPerSec.description: Group Conflicts/sec is the rate at which group registration received by the WINS server resulted in conflicts with records in the database.

winsSrvrGroupRegsPerSec.name: winsSrvrGroupRegsPerSec
winsSrvrGroupRegsPerSec.description: Group Registrations/sec is the rate at which group registration are received by the WINS server.

winsSrvrGroupRenewalsPerSec.name: winsSrvrGroupRenewalsPerSec
winsSrvrGroupRenewalsPerSec.description: Group Renewals/sec is the rate at which group renewals are received by the WINS server.

winsSrvrQueriesPerSec.name: winsSrvrQueriesPerSec
winsSrvrQueriesPerSec.description: Total Number of Queries/sec is the rate at which queries are received by the WINS server.

winsSrvrReleasesPerSec.name: winsSrvrReleasesPerSec
winsSrvrReleasesPerSec.description: Total Number of Releases/sec is the rate at which releases are received by the WINS server.

winsSrvrTotalNumConflictsPerSec.name: winsSrvrTotalNumConflictsPerSec
winsSrvrTotalNumConflictsPerSec.description: Total Number of Conflicts/sec is the sum of the Unique and Group conflicts per sec. This is the total rate at which conflicts were seen by the WINS server.

winsSrvrTotalNumRegsPerSec.name: winsSrvrTotalNumRegsPerSec
winsSrvrTotalNumRegsPerSec.description: Total Number of Registrations/sec is the sum of the Unique and Group registrations per sec. This is the total rate at which registration are received by the WINS server.

winsSrvrTotalNumRenewalsPerSec.name: winsSrvrTotalNumRenewalsPerSec
winsSrvrTotalNumRenewalsPerSec.description: Total Number of Renewals/sec is the sum of the Unique and Group renewals per sec. This is the total rate at which renewals are received by the WINS server.

winsSrvrUniqueConflictsPerSec.name: winsSrvrUniqueConflictsPerSec
winsSrvrUniqueConflictsPerSec.description: Unique Conflicts/sec is the rate at which unique registrations/renewals received by the WINS server resulted in conflicts with records in the database.

winsSrvrUniqueRegsPerSec.name: winsSrvrUniqueRegsPerSec
winsSrvrUniqueRegsPerSec.description: Unique Registrations/sec is the rate at which unique registration are received by the WINS server.

winsSrvrUniqueRenewalsPerSec.name: winsSrvrUniqueRenewalsPerSec
winsSrvrUniqueRenewalsPerSec.description: Unique Renewals/sec is the rate at which unique renewals are received by the WINS server.

wmiObjects.name: wmiObjects
wmiObjects.description: Number of WMI High Performance provider returned by WMI Adapter

wmiObjectsHiPerfValidity.name: wmiObjectsHiPerfValidity
wmiObjectsHiPerfValidity.description: Shows if High Performance Classes are valid

bnuBITSDownloadBlockSizeBytes.description: Size of the next download block for BITS

bnuEstBWAvailRemoteBitsPerSec.description: Estimated bandwidth available to the remote system (Bits/sec)

bnuIGDSpeedBitsPerSec.name: bnuIGDSpeedBitsPerSec
bnuIGDSpeedBitsPerSec.description: Estimate of the IGD's Internet connection speed (Bits/Sec)

bnuNetcardSpeedBitsPerSec.name: bnuNetcardSpeedBitsPerSec
bnuNetcardSpeedBitsPerSec.description: Estimate of the local netcard's speed (Bits/Sec)

bnuPercentIGDFree.name: bnuPercentIGDFree
bnuPercentIGDFree.description: Estimate of most recent percent IGD Internet connection utilization

bnuPercentNetcardFree.name: bnuPercentNetcardFree
bnuPercentNetcardFree.description: Estimate of most recent percent network interface utilization

advDatabaseTable.name: advDatabaseTable
advDatabaseTable.description: Database provides performance statistics for each process using the ESE high performance embedded database management system.

advDatabaseEntry.name: advDatabaseEntry
advDatabaseEntry.description: Performance information for one particular instance of 'Database' object.

adbDatabaseCachePercentHit.name: adbDatabaseCachePercentHit
adbDatabaseCachePercentHit.description: Database Cache % Hit is the percentage of database file page requests that were fulfilled by the database cache without causing a file operation. If this percentage is too low, the database cache size may be too small.

adbDatabaseCacheSize.name: adbDatabaseCacheSize
adbDatabaseCacheSize.description: Database Cache Size is the amount of system memory used by the database cache manager to hold commonly used information from the database file(s) to prevent file operations. If the database cache size seems to be too small for optimal performance and there is very little available memory on the system (see Memory/Available Bytes), adding more memory to the system may increase performance. If there is a lot of available memory on the system and the database cache size is not growing beyond a certain point, the database cache size may be capped at an artificially low limit. Increasing this limit may increase performance.

adbDatabaseCacheSizeMB.name: adbDatabaseCacheSizeMB
adbDatabaseCacheSizeMB.description: Database Cache Size (MB) is the amount of system memory (in MegaBytes) used by the database cache manager to hold commonly used information from the database file(s) to prevent file operations. If the database cache size seems to be too small for optimal performance and there is very little available memory on the system (see Memory/Available Bytes), adding more memory to the system may increase performance. If there is a lot of available memory on the system and the database cache size is not growing beyond a certain point, the database cache size may be capped at an artificially low limit. Increasing this limit may increase performance.

adbDatabasePageEvictionsPerSec.name: adbDatabasePageEvictionsPerSec
adbDatabasePageEvictionsPerSec.description: Database Page Evictions/sec is the rate that database file page requests that require the database cache manager to allocate a new page from the database cache force another database page out of the cache. The eviction count is charged when the page is allocated and not when the previous owner of that page was actually evicted from the cache. If this rate is too high, the database cache size may be too small.

adbDatabasePageFaultStallsPerSec.name: adbDatabasePageFaultStallsPerSec
adbDatabasePageFaultStallsPerSec.description: Database Page Fault Stalls/sec is the rate of page faults that cannot be serviced because there are no pages available for allocation from the database cache. If this counter is non-zero most of the time, the clean threshold may be too low.

adbDatabasePageFaultsPerSec.name: adbDatabasePageFaultsPerSec
adbDatabasePageFaultsPerSec.description: Database Page Faults/sec is the rate that database file page requests require the database cache manager to allocate a new page from the database cache.

adbIPerODatabaseReadsAvgLatency.name: adbIPerODatabaseReadsAvgLatency
adbIPerODatabaseReadsAvgLatency.description: I/O Database Reads Average Latency is the average length of time, in milliseconds, per database read operation.

adbIPerODatabaseReadsPerSec.name: adbIPerODatabaseReadsPerSec
adbIPerODatabaseReadsPerSec.description: I/O Database Reads/sec is the rate of database read operations completed.

adbIPerODatabaseWritesAvgLatency.name: adbIPerODatabaseWritesAvgLatency
adbIPerODatabaseWritesAvgLatency.description: I/O Database Writes Average Latency is the average length of time, in milliseconds, per database write operation.

adbIPerODatabaseWritesPerSec.name: adbIPerODatabaseWritesPerSec
adbIPerODatabaseWritesPerSec.description: I/O Database Writes/sec is the rate of database write operations completed.

adbIPerOLogReadsPerSec.name: adbIPerOLogReadsPerSec
adbIPerOLogReadsPerSec.description: I/O Log Reads/sec is the rate of logfile read operations completed.

adbIPerOLogWritesAverageLatency.name: adbIPerOLogWritesAverageLatency
adbIPerOLogWritesAverageLatency.description: I/O Log Writes Average Latency is the average length of time, in milliseconds, per logfile write operation.

adbIPerOLogWritesPerSec.name: adbIPerOLogWritesPerSec
adbIPerOLogWritesPerSec.description: I/O Log Writes/sec is the rate of logfile write operations completed.

adbLogBytesWritePerSec.name: adbLogBytesWritePerSec
adbLogBytesWritePerSec.description: Log Bytes Write per second is the rate bytes are written to the log.

adbLogRecordStallsPerSec.name: adbLogRecordStallsPerSec
adbLogRecordStallsPerSec.description: Log Record Stalls/sec is the number of log records that cannot be added to the log buffers per second because they are full. If this counter is non-zero most of the time, the log buffer size may be a bottleneck.

adbLogThreadsWaiting.name: adbLogThreadsWaiting
adbLogThreadsWaiting.description: Log Threads Waiting is the number of threads waiting for their data to be written to the log in order to complete an update of the database. If this number is too high, the log may be a bottleneck.

adbLogWritesPerSec.name: adbLogWritesPerSec
adbLogWritesPerSec.description: Log Writes/sec is the number of times the log buffers are written to the log file(s) per second. If this number approaches the maximum write rate for the media holding the log file(s), the log may be a bottleneck.

adbPagesConverted.name: adbPagesConverted
adbPagesConverted.description: Pages Converted is the count of database pages that have been converted from an older format

adbPagesConvertedPerSec.name: adbPagesConvertedPerSec
adbPagesConvertedPerSec.description: Pages Converted/sec is the count of times per second a database page is converted from an older database format

adbRecordsConverted.name: adbRecordsConverted
adbRecordsConverted.description: Records Converted is the count of database records that have been converted from an older format

adbRecordsConvertedPerSec.name: adbRecordsConvertedPerSec
adbRecordsConvertedPerSec.description: Records Converted/sec is the count of times per second a database record is converted from an older database format

adbSessionsPercentUsed.name: adbSessionsPercentUsed
adbSessionsPercentUsed.description: Sessions % Used is the percentage of database sessions currently open for use by client threads. [Dev Only]

adbSessionsInUse.name: adbSessionsInUse
adbSessionsInUse.description: Sessions In Use is the number of database sessions currently open for use by client threads. [Dev Only]

adbTableOpenCachePercentHit.name: adbTableOpenCachePercentHit
adbTableOpenCachePercentHit.description: Table Open Cache % Hit is the percentage of database tables opened using cached schema information. If this percentage is too low, the table cache size may be too small.

adbTableOpenCacheHitsPerSec.name: adbTableOpenCacheHitsPerSec
adbTableOpenCacheHitsPerSec.description: Table Open Cache Hits/sec is the number of database tables opened using cached schema information per second. If this rate is too low, the table cache size may be too small.

adbTableOpenCacheMissesPerSec.name: adbTableOpenCacheMissesPerSec
adbTableOpenCacheMissesPerSec.description: Table Open Cache Misses/sec is the number of database tables opened without using cached schema information per second. If this rate is too high, the table cache size may be too small.

adbTableOpensPerSec.name: adbTableOpensPerSec
adbTableOpensPerSec.description: Table Opens/sec is the number of database tables opened per second.

adbVersionBucketsAllocated.name: adbVersionBucketsAllocated
adbVersionBucketsAllocated.description: Total number of version buckets allocated

adbiLogBytesWritePerSec.description: Log Bytes Write per second is the rate bytes are written to the log.

adbiLogGenCheckpointDepth.description: Log Generation Checkpoint Depth represents the amount of work, in count of log files, that will need to be redone or undone to the database file(s) if the process crashes.

adbiLogGenCheckpointDepthMax.name: adbiLogGenCheckpointDepthMax
adbiLogGenCheckpointDepthMax.description: Log Record Stalls/sec is the number of log records that cannot be added to the log buffers per second because they are full. If this counter is non-zero most of the time, the log buffer size may be a bottleneck.

adbiLogGenLossResiliencyDepth.name: adbiLogGenLossResiliencyDepth
adbiLogGenLossResiliencyDepth.description: Log Threads Waiting is the number of threads waiting for their data to be written to the log in order to complete an update of the database. If this number is too high, the log may be a bottleneck.

adbiPagesConvertedPerSec.description: Records Converted/sec is the count of times per second a database record is converted from an older database format

adbiRecordsConvertedPerSec.description: Sessions In Use is the number of database sessions currently open for use by client threads. [Dev Only]

adbiSessionsPercentUsed.description: Streaming Backup Pages Read/sec is the rate of database read operationsperformed for the purpose of streaming backups.

adbiSessionsInUse.name: adbiSessionsInUse
adbiSessionsInUse.description: Table Open Cache % Hit is the percentage of database tables opened using cached schema information. If this percentage is too low, the table cache size may be too small.

adbiStreamBackupPagesReadPerSec.name: adbiStreamBackupPagesReadPerSec
adbiStreamBackupPagesReadPerSec.description: Table Open Cache Hits/sec is the number of database tables opened using cached schema information per second. If this rate is too low, the table cache size may be too small.

genericIKEAndAuthIP.name: genericIKEAndAuthIP
genericIKEAndAuthIP.description: Generic IKE and AuthIP is the set of Internet Protocol security (IPsec) Internet Key Exchange (IKE) and Authenticated IP (AuthIP) counters that are generic and do not apply to a specific Internet Protocol version.

giaipAuthIPMainModeNegotTime.name: giaipAuthIPMainModeNegotTime
giaipAuthIPMainModeNegotTime.description: AuthIP Main Mode Negotiation Time is the number of milliseconds taken for the last Authenticated IP Main Mode security association negotiated.

giaipAuthIPQuickModeNegotTime.name: giaipAuthIPQuickModeNegotTime
giaipAuthIPQuickModeNegotTime.description: AuthIP Quick Mode Negotiation Time is the number of milliseconds taken for the last Authenticated IP Quick Mode security association negotiated.

giaipExtendedModeNegotiationTime.name: giaipExtendedModeNegotiationTime
giaipExtendedModeNegotiationTime.description: Extended Mode Negotiation Time is the number of milliseconds taken for the last Extended Mode security association negotiated.

giaipFailedNegotiations.name: giaipFailedNegotiations
giaipFailedNegotiations.description: Failed Negotiations is the number of failed negotiations for IKE and AuthIP since IPsec was last started.

giaipFailedNegotiationsPerSec.name: giaipFailedNegotiationsPerSec
giaipFailedNegotiationsPerSec.description: Failed Negotiations per second is the rate of failed negotiations attempted for IKE and AuthIP.

giaipIKEMainModeNegotiationTime.name: giaipIKEMainModeNegotiationTime
giaipIKEMainModeNegotiationTime.description: IKE Main Mode Negotiation Time is the number of milliseconds taken for the last IKE Main Mode security association negotiated.

giaipIKEQuickModeNegotiationTime.name: giaipIKEQuickModeNegotiationTime
giaipIKEQuickModeNegotiationTime.description: IKE Quick Mode Negotiation Time is the number of milliseconds taken for the last IKE Quick Mode security association negotiated.

giaipInvalidPacketReceivedPerSec.name: giaipInvalidPacketReceivedPerSec
giaipInvalidPacketReceivedPerSec.description: Invalid Packets Received per second is the rate at which invalid IPsec packets are being received.

giaipPacketsReceivedPerSec.name: giaipPacketsReceivedPerSec

securityPerProcessStatisticTable.name: securityPerProcessStatisticTable
securityPerProcessStatisticTable.description: These counters track the number of security resources and handles used per process.

securityPerProcessStatisticEntry.name: securityPerProcessStatisticEntry
securityPerProcessStatisticEntry.description: Performance information for one particular instance of 'Security Per-Process Statistics' object.

sppsContextHandles.name: sppsContextHandles
sppsContextHandles.description: This counter tracks the number of context handles in use by a given process. Context handles are associated with security contexts established between a client application and a remote peer.

sppsCredentialHandles.name: sppsCredentialHandles
sppsCredentialHandles.description: This counter tracks the number of credential handles in use by a given process. Credential handles are handles to pre-existing credentials, such as a password, that are associated with a user and are established through a system logon.

securitySystemWideStatistics.name: securitySystemWideStatistics
securitySystemWideStatistics.description: These counters track authentication performance on a per second basis.

sswsActiveSChannelSessionCache.name: sswsActiveSChannelSessionCache
sswsActiveSChannelSessionCache.description: This counter tracks the number of Secure Sockets Layer (SSL) entries that are currently stored in the secure channel (Schannel) session cache and that are currently in use. The Schannel session cache stores information about successfully established sessions, such as SSL session IDs. Clients can use this information to reconnect to a server without performaing a full SSL handshake.

sswsDigestAuthentications.name: sswsDigestAuthentications
sswsDigestAuthentications.description: This counter tracks the number of Digest authentications that are being processed per second.

sswsKDCASRequests.name: sswsKDCASRequests
sswsKDCASRequests.description: This counter tracks the number of Autonomous System (AS) requests that are being processed by the Key Distribution Center (KDC) per second. Clients use AS requests to obtain a ticket-granting ticket.

sswsKDCTGSRequests.name: sswsKDCTGSRequests
sswsKDCTGSRequests.description: This counter tracks the number of ticket-granting service (TGS) requests that are being processed by the Key Distribution Center (KDC) per second. Clients use these TGS requests to obtain a service ticket, which allows a client to access resources on other computers.

sswsKerberosAuthentications.name: sswsKerberosAuthentications
sswsKerberosAuthentications.description: This counter tracks the number of times that clients use a ticket to authenticate to this computer per second.

sswsNTLMAuthentications.name: sswsNTLMAuthentications
sswsNTLMAuthentications.description: This counter tracks the number of NTLM authentications processed by this computer per second.

sswsSSLClientSideFullHandshakes.name: sswsSSLClientSideFullHandshakes
sswsSSLClientSideFullHandshakes.description: This counter tracks the number of Secure Sockets Layer (SSL) full client-side handshakes that are being processed per second. During a handshake, signals are exchanged to acknowledge that communication can occur between computers or other devices.

sswsSSLClientSideReconHandshakes.name: sswsSSLClientSideReconHandshakes
sswsSSLClientSideReconHandshakes.description: This counter tracks the number of Secure Sockets Layer (SSL) client-side reconnect handshakes that are being processed per second. Reconnect handshakes allow session keys from previous SSL sessions to be used to resume a client/server connection, and they require less memory to process than full handshakes.

sswsSSLServerSideFullHandshakes.name: sswsSSLServerSideFullHandshakes
sswsSSLServerSideFullHandshakes.description: This counter tracks the number of Secure Sockets Layer (SSL) full server-side handshakes that are being processed per second. During a handshake, signals are exchanged to acknowledge that communication can occur between computers or other devices.

sswsSSLServerSideReconHandshakes.name: sswsSSLServerSideReconHandshakes
sswsSSLServerSideReconHandshakes.description: This counter tracks the number of Secure Sockets Layer (SSL) server-side reconnect handshakes that are being processed per second. Reconnect handshakes allow session keys from previous SSL sessions to be used to resume a client/server connection, and they require less memory to process than full handshakes.

sswsSchannelSessionCacheEntries.name: sswsSchannelSessionCacheEntries
sswsSchannelSessionCacheEntries.description: This counter tracks the number of Secure Sockets Layer (SSL) entries that are currently stored in the secure channel (Schannel) session cache. The Schannel session cache stores information about successfully established sessions, such as SSL session IDs. Clients can use this information to reconnect to a server without performing a full SSL handshake.

adnAppl2CachePctMachMemLimUsed.name: adnAppl2CachePctMachMemLimUsed
adnAppl2CachePctMachMemLimUsed.description: The amount of physical memory used by the machine divided by the physical memory limit for the cache, as a percentage. When this reaches 100%, half of the cache entries will be forcibly removed. The __Total__ instance is the average of all instances, and therefore cannot be used to determine when cache entries will be forcibly removed.

adnAppl2CachePctProcMemLimUsed.name: adnAppl2CachePctProcMemLimUsed
adnAppl2CachePctProcMemLimUsed.description: The value of private bytes for the worker process divided by the private bytes memory limit for the cache, as a percentage. When this reaches 100%, half of the cache entries will be forcibly removed. The __Total__ instance is the average of all instances, and therefore cannot be used to determine when cache entries will be forcibly removed.

dsDRAInCmpBtwSiteBfrCmpSinceBoot.description: Original size in bytes of inbound compressed replication data (size before compression, from DSAs in other sites).

dsDRAInCmpBtwSitesBeforCmpPerSec.description: Original size in bytes of inbound compressed replication data (size before compression, from DSAs in other sites).

dsDRAInNotCmpWithinSiteSinceBoot.name: dsDRAInNotCmpWithinSiteSinceBoot
dsDRAInNotCmpWithinSiteSinceBoot.description: Number of bytes replicated in that were not compressed at the source (i.e., from DSAs in the same site).

dsDRAInNotCmpWithinSitePerSec.name: dsDRAInNotCmpWithinSitePerSec
dsDRAInNotCmpWithinSitePerSec.description: Number of bytes replicated in that were not compressed at the source (i.e., from DSAs in the same site).

dsDRAInBytesTotalSinceBoot.name: dsDRAInBytesTotalSinceBoot
dsDRAInBytesTotalSinceBoot.description: Total number of bytes replicated in. Sum of the number of uncompressed bytes (never compressed) and the number of compressed bytes (after compression).

dsDRAInBytesTotalPerSec.name: dsDRAInBytesTotalPerSec
dsDRAInBytesTotalPerSec.description: Total number of bytes replicated in. Sum of the number of uncompressed bytes (never compressed) and the number of compressed bytes (after compression).

dsDRAInFullSyncObjectsRemaining.name: dsDRAInFullSyncObjectsRemaining
dsDRAInFullSyncObjectsRemaining.description: Number of objects remaining until the full sync completes (when set).

dsDRAInLinkValueUpdRemainInPkt.name: dsDRAInLinkValueUpdRemainInPkt
dsDRAInLinkValueUpdRemainInPkt.description: The number of link value updates received in the current directory replication update packet that have not yet been applied to the local server.

dsDRAInObjectUpdRemainInPkt.name: dsDRAInObjectUpdRemainInPkt
dsDRAInObjectUpdRemainInPkt.description: The number of object updates received in the current directory replication update packet that have not yet been applied to the local server.

dsDRAInObjectsAppliedPerSec.name: dsDRAInObjectsAppliedPerSec
dsDRAInObjectsAppliedPerSec.description: The rate at which replication updates received from replication partners are applied by the local directory service. This count excludes changes that are received but not applied (e.g., when the change is already present). This indicates how much replication update activity is occuring on the server as a result of changes generated on other servers.

dsDRAInObjectsFilteredPerSec.name: dsDRAInObjectsFilteredPerSec
dsDRAInObjectsFilteredPerSec.description: Number of objects received from inbound replication partners that contained no updates that needed to be applied.

dsDRAInObjectsPerSec.name: dsDRAInObjectsPerSec
dsDRAInObjectsPerSec.description: No of objects received from neighbors through inbound replication.

dsDRAInPropertiesAppliedPerSec.name: dsDRAInPropertiesAppliedPerSec
dsDRAInPropertiesAppliedPerSec.description: No of properties that are updated due to incoming property winning the reconciliation logic.

dsDRAInPropertiesFilteredPerSec.name: dsDRAInPropertiesFilteredPerSec
dsDRAInPropertiesFilteredPerSec.description: No of property changes that are received during the replication that we have already seen.

dsDRAInPropertiesTotalPerSec.name: dsDRAInPropertiesTotalPerSec
dsDRAInPropertiesTotalPerSec.description: Total number of object properties received from inbound replication partners.

dsDRAInTotalUpdRemainInPkt.name: dsDRAInTotalUpdRemainInPkt
dsDRAInTotalUpdRemainInPkt.description: The number of total (link values + object) updates received in the current directory replication update packet that have not yet been applied to the local server.

dsDRAInValuesDNsOnlyPerSec.name: dsDRAInValuesDNsOnlyPerSec
dsDRAInValuesDNsOnlyPerSec.description: Number of object property values received from inbound replication partners that are Distinguished Names; i.e., that reference other objects. DN-values, such as group or distribution list memberships, are generally more expensive to apply than other kinds of values.

dsDRAInValuesTotalPerSec.name: dsDRAInValuesTotalPerSec
dsDRAInValuesTotalPerSec.description: Total number of object property values received from inbound replication partners. Each inbound object has one or more properties, and each property has zero or more values. Zero values indicates property removal.

dsDRAOutCmpBtwSitesAftCmpSinceBt.description: Compressed size in bytes of outbound compressed replication data (size after compression, from DSAs in other sites).

dsDRAOutCmpBtwSitesAftCmpPerSec.name: dsDRAOutCmpBtwSitesAftCmpPerSec
dsDRAOutCmpBtwSitesAftCmpPerSec.description: Compressed size in bytes of outbound compressed replication data (size after compression, from DSAs in other sites).

dsDRAOutCmpBtwSitesBfrCmpSinceBt.name: dsDRAOutCmpBtwSitesBfrCmpSinceBt
dsDRAOutCmpBtwSitesBfrCmpSinceBt.description: Original size in bytes of outbound compressed replication data (size before compression, from DSAs in other sites).

dsDRAOutCmpBtwSitesBfrCmpPerSec.description: Original size in bytes of outbound compressed replication data (size before compression, from DSAs in other sites).

dsDRAOutNotCmpWithinSitePerSec.name: dsDRAOutNotCmpWithinSitePerSec
dsDRAOutNotCmpWithinSitePerSec.description: Number of bytes replicated out that were not compressed (i.e., from DSAs in the same site).

dsDRAOutboundBytesTotalSinceBoot.description: Total number of bytes replicated out. Sum of the number of uncompressed bytes (never compressed) and the number of compressed bytes (after compression).
